<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Business-Education     10-08 0542</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business-Education,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Educators Rap Bush, Dukakis On Education Priorities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOT SPRINGS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Educators addressing the nation's top
business leaders say both presidential candidates have failed to
fulfill their promises to make education a priority of their
campaigns.
   Republican George Bush has said he wants to be known as ``the
education president'' and Democrat Michael Dukakis has said ``no
issue ... means more to me.''
   However, over the past year there's been ``a strange silence,''
said Ernest L. Boyer, president of the Carnegie Foundation for the
Advancement of Teaching. ``A few little pieces have come along,
revolving mainly around college loans and grants, but I have not
seen a coherent program from either candidate.''
   ``I am disappointed with the lack of a sense of urgency,'' said
Marian Wright Edelman, president of the Children's Defense Fund,
which takes a liberal approach to family issues.
   ``Never have we heard so much discussion. But the proof of the
pudding is in the concrete proposals, the willingness to invest,''
she said.
   Boyer, Edelman and other education leaders spoke Friday during
private sessions of the Business Council, composed of 62 chief
executives of the country's biggest companies. They talked with
reporters afterward.
   The executives were gathered for their twice-a-year meeting in
this resort town in the mountains of western Virginia.
   Albert Shanker, president of the 665,000-member American
Federation of Teachers, said he agreed that neither candidate had a
well-developed education program, but he said he preferred Dukakis
to Bush because the Republican tilts toward providing federal
assistance to private schools.
   ``For us that's a life and death difference. If you move away
from the public schools ... that's abandoning the major institution
we have in our society for improvement of education,'' he said.
   However, former Delaware Gov. Pete du Pont, who ran
unsuccessfully for the Republican presidential nomination, said
Bush should more strongly emphasize using free market competition
to improve education.
   ``The school system is terrified of (competition). They have a
government monopoly. They don't have to compete for their kids. Why
would they want to change? The problem is, of course, they're
giving everyone a lousy education,'' he said.
   Both Boyer and Edelman said they were encouraged that business
leaders recognized education's importance to the future of the
country.
   ``They are voices that are listened to (by politicians). They're
not going to listen to a third grade teacher. They are going to
listen to the president of a major corporation. Even the president
of the United States will answer a phone call from the people in
this conference,'' Boyer said.
   Also scheduled to speak to the business executives finishing a
two-day conference today were Paul Volcker, a forme chairman of the
Federal Reserve Board; Commerce Secretary C. William Verity; Sen.
Lawton Chiles, D-Fla., and Rep. William Gray, D-Pa., the chairmen
of the congressional budget committees, and Drew Lewis and Robert
S. Strauss, the co-chairmen of a blue-ribbon commission studying
the budget deficit.
   The council, formed in 1933 as an advisory panel to the
Department of Commerce, selected Roger B. Smith, chairman of
General Motors Corp., to serve as its chairman in 1989 and 1990. He
replaces S.D. Bechtel Jr., chairman of Bechtel Group Inc., a
worldwide construction firm.
</TEXT>
