<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Panama     10-08 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Panama Declares Election Season Open</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALINA GUERRERO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Friday declared the
campaign season open for general elections to be held May 7 of next
year and said the ballot will not be affected by strained
diplomatic relations with the United States.
   A president and two vice presidents will be elected by simple
majority of votes in May, to serve five-year terms beginning June 7.
   Elections for the legislative National Assembly and local
offices will be held June 4.
   The Electoral Tribunal said in a communique the campaign
schedule will be respected despite Panama's political and economic
crises.
   The United States has imposed economic sanctions and diplomatic
pressure on Panama trying to force Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega to
resign as the Defense Forces commander and as such, Panama's de
facto ruler.
   Noriega is under U.S. indictment on drug trafficking and money
laundering charges, which he denies. When President Eric Arturo
Delvalle tried to fire Noriega last February, Delvalle himself was
dismissed by the Noriega-controlled National Assembly.
   The Reagan administration still recognizes Delvalle as Panama's
legitimate president. U.S. economic sanctions have helped push
Panama's economy into its worst depression since the 1930s.
   Under election code changes approved by the assembly in August,
mayoral elections were eliminated in 68 towns and cities. Beginning
in 1989, the president will appoint mayors.
   The changes also require public office-holders who are
presidential candidates to resign three months before the election.
   Noriega has given no indication whether he plans to resign as
Defense Forces commander and run for president as standard-bearer
of the governing Democratic Revolutionary Party.
   Since a military coup in 1968, the presidency has been a
ceremonial post dominated by the armed forces. Nicolas Ardito
Barletta ran as the government candidate and won the presidential
election in 1984, the first in 16 years. He resigned under pressure
in 1985 over differences with the Defense Forces.
   With the military's support, Delvalle succeeded Barletta.
   The opposition has not yet said whether it will take part in the
election.
   Legally registered opposition parties include the Authentic
Panamanian Party, the Christian Democratic Party, the Liberal
Republican Movement, the Labor Party, the Republican Party and the
National Action Party.
   More than 1.1 million Panamanians are registered to vote in May.
In the 1984 presidential elections, 917,000 voters were registered.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
