<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BeanMurder     10-08 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bean Murder,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Killer of Heir to Baked Bean Fortune Gets 30 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A trucker convicted of murdering the heir
to the Burnham & Morrill baked bean fortune was sentenced Friday to
30 years in prison during an emotional hearing in which the
victim's son urged the judge to be lenient.
   James H. Savage Sr., 53, of Gardiner, faced a minimum of 25
years in prison for the slaying of Charles Sumner Morrill III, who
was shot four times at his farm in North Baldwin on Nov. 7, 1987.
   Justice Paul Fritzsche called the incident ``a horrible
tragedy.''
   Savage had maintained that he acted in self-defense when
Morrill, 51, attacked him after Savage arrived at the farm to
discuss his recently ended 14-month affair with Morrill's wife,
Jessie.
   The prosecution had claimed that Savage, armed with a loaded
pistol, had intended to provoke Morrill.
   His voice cracking, Savage told the judge he had been used by
Mrs. Morrill. ``I gave up everything I had,'' he said.
   The victim's son, Charles Sumner Morrill IV, backed up Savage's
account, saying he had told the truth about his stepmother. ``He
was a pawn, just like my father was a pawn,'' Morrill said.
   Morrill urged the judge to impose the 25-year minimum prison
term. The prosecution sought 30 years.
   Morrill and Savage were members of a bluegrass band that had
broken up earlier last year.
</TEXT>
