<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Strauss-Service     10-08 0225</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Strauss-Service,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World Dignitaries Attend Strauss Memorial Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MUNICH, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Heads of state and dignitaries from
around the world attended memorial services Friday for Bavarian
leader Franz Josef Strauss, one of West Germany's most dynamic and
colorful politicians.
   Strauss, 73, governor of Bavaria and chairman of the
conservative Christian Social Union party, died Monday in
Regensburg.
   He was an original founder of West Germany when its government
was formed in 1949, and his influence reached far beyond its
borders.
   Thousands of prominent politicians, dignitaries, industrialists,
and religious leaders attended memorial proceedings, including
former U.S. Secretary of State Henry Kissinger, President Pieter
Botha of South Africa and Soviet Deputy Premier Ivan Silayev.
   Proceedings began with a Roman Catholic Mass in Munich's
Liebfrauendom Cathedral, followed by a state memorial service in
nearby Wittelsbacher Residence building and a funeral procession
through the city.
   Strauss' daughter and two sons and his sister attended. His wife
Marianne died in 1984 in a car accident.
   West German President Richard von Weizsaecker and Chancellor
Helmut Kohl delivered eulogies.
   At the Mass, Cardinal Friedrich Wetter, archbishop of Munich and
Friesin, read aloud a telegram from the Vatican, in which Pope John
Paul II praised Strauss as a ``great Christian statesman.''
   Strauss was to be buried Saturday alongside his wife in Rott am
Inn, a small Bavarian village near Rosenheim.
</TEXT>
