<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 0028EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Reagan     10-08 0437</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Invokes Quayle's Name More Often</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan is broadening his campaign
stump speech to heap praise on besieged Republican vice
presidential candidate Dan Quayle.
   During the latest in a series of campaign-style trips aimed at
helping George Bush keep the White House in Republican hands,
Reagan on several occasions Friday put Quayle's name in a favorable
light. This was in addition to the usual Reagan plaudits for Bush.
   The president departed from the text of a dinner speech to tell
his audience that ``someone I know and respect came through for us
and all Americans the other night.''
   ``I have to say, I wasn't surprised,'' Reagan said of Quayle's
performance in debate with Democratic rival Lloyd Bentsen.
   ``Sure, the Washington establishment was betting against him,
but I can tell you, the smart money was riding on a great senator
by the name of Dan Quayle,'' he added.
   ``I tell you, he got my vote. How about you?'' the president
asked, bringing applause from the audience.
   Reagan had seldom mentioned Quayle's name in recent campaign
outings, but White House officials were unwilling to talk about the
apparent change in strategy.
   The kind words for Quayle on Friday started the moment Reagan
left the White House in the morning en route to Detroit, when he
made mention of the Indiana senator while commenting on the latest
drop in unemployment figures.
   ``We've talked about the record 70 months of economic expansion,
but these figures tell the real story that people can understand,''
he said. ``And that's what George Bush and Dan Quayle stand for and
it's what the administration has worked out for the last eight
years.''
   Once he arrived in Detroit, the president continued the
pro-Quayle statements he had commenced Thursday in the wake of
criticism of the Indiana senator's performance in Wednesday's vice
presidential debate.
   Speaking to a luncheon of business executives in Macomb County,
Reagan said that ``one thing's even clearer to me after watching
the debate Wednesday night: the Bush-Quayle ticket will continue
the policies of peace and prosperity that have _ as Dan said _ made
this great nation `the envy of the world.'''
   Then, in his address to a $1,000-a-plate fund-raising dinner,
Reagan repeated that refrain.
   The president had talked glowingly of Quayle in the days
immediately following the Republican National Convention in August,
tossing the senator's name prominently into a speech he made Aug.
24 in a joint appearance with Bush in Los Angeles.
   But Reagan in the past few weeks had not alluded to Quayle in
these stump speeches.
</TEXT>
