<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 0030EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-BRF--WaywardWarbler     10-08 0152</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Wayward Warbler,0155</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Birds Of A Feather Get Lost Together</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIR ISLE, Scotland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A windswept and probably weary
Blackburnian warbler has been spotted on a Scottish island, the
first recorded sighting of the tiny American bird in Europe, a
wildlife warden says.
   The bird flew 3,000 miles across the Atlantic Ocean, apparently
swept off course by westerly gales while migrating to South America
for the winter, said Nick Riddiford, a warden at the Fair Isle Bird
Observatory.
   It was found recently on Fair Isle, midway between the islands
of Orkney and Shetland north of the Scottish mainland, he said.
   Another trans-Atlantic traveler, a northern oriole, arrived in
the southwest English county of Cornwall Tuesday and an American
robin has been spotted on the Isle of Wight, off the southern coast
of England.
   Much of Britain has been swept by high winds blowing in from the
Atlantic in recent days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881008-0014 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 0031EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Candidates-Speech     10-08 0595</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Candidates-Speech,610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Speech Coach Says Both Candidates Have Improved Their Oratory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA WOLFSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``There is no index of character so
sure as the voice,'' British statesman and orator Benjamin Disraeli
once said.
   If U.S. presidential candidates were judged by that standard
alone, neither Republican George Bush nor Democrat Michael Dukakis
would have a chance of winning the election, in the view of speech
pathologist Lillian Glass.
   ``It's about time the candidates begin to work with
consultants,'' she said. ``They have to realize, we don't live in a
democracy in terms of appearance.'' Politicians often are judged by
how they look and sound, not by their policies, she said.
   Ms. Glass, 34, the author of ``Talk to Win: Six Steps to a
Successful Vocal Image,'' has been analyzing the voices of Bush and
Dukakis since the early stages of their campaigns.
   Prior to the Republican National Convention last July, Ms. Glass
said that Bush's high-pitched, nasal voice negated his strong
physical presence and made him appear ``wimpy.'' Dukakis, she said,
spoke in a monotone and was unemotional.
   ``An election can be lost solely on how you sound,'' Ms. Glass
said.
   Both candidates, however, demonstrated a vastly improved
speaking style during their first debate on Sept. 25, she said.
   ``Bush is not perfect ... but he's lost the wimp factor,'' Ms.
Glass said after the debate, noting his slower, more methodical
approach, lower-pitch and stronger inflection.
   The changes in the vice president, for the most part, are being
attributed to the coaching of Roger Ailes, a former New York
television producer who serves as the campaign's senior media
advisor in Washington.
   Ailes denied molding Bush's image. He said any changes are in
the eyes of the public.
   ``People are starting to view him as a president and not as
(President) Reagan's assistant,'' he said. ``I mean the man is the
vice president of the United States. You don't get there because
three months ago you decided to do something about your voice.''
   Dukakis has a lot of potential as an orator but has not yet
mastered a presidential style, Ms. Glass said.
   ``He didn't go up as much at the end of sentences like he used
to,'' she said after the Sept. 25 debate. ``He had better diction
and less staccato in his voice.''
   As for the diction of the vice presidential candidates, there is
no comparison, said Ms. Glass.
   ``Dukakis' best asset is Lloyd Bentsen,'' she said. ``He blows
everybody away with his beautiful projection, posture and good
inflection. His security and warmth come across.''
   The Texas senator has a take-charge persona that Dukakis can
learn from, Ms. Glass said.
   Indiana Sen. Dan Quayle, on the other hand, comes across
unsophisticated and ``twice as wimpy'' as Bush ever did, the speech
therapist said.
   ``He's a good-looking man with a high, nasal voice and that
doesn't reflect a lot of self-confidence.''
   ``Bush looks like a star and is beginning to sound more like a
star,'' she said. ``If he had a star running mate, it would
certainly help the ticket be more powerful.''
   Ms. Glass said all the candidates should use Reagan as a role
model.
   ``Whether you agree with his politics or not, you feel his
compassion and dedication to the country,'' she said. ``He has a
very calming effect.''
   What makes Reagan so good?
   ``His excellent posture, his body movement, how he uses the
camera,'' Ms. Glass said. ``It's his friend. When he's angry, you
see it. When he's up, it's reflected in his voice.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
