<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Nicaragua-LaPrensa     10-08 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-La Prensa,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>La Prensa Publishes Government Warning</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaragua's only opposition newspaper,
La Prensa, published a government notice in its Friday editions
that condemned what it called the newspaper's ``defamatory''
reporting of the shootings of three labor activists.
   The Interior Ministry notice criticized a La Prensa editorial
Thursday that accompanied the texts of two government protests of
the newspaper's reporting of the Sunday shootings. La Prensa
printed the protests under government order.
   Friday's notice, was an ``admonition.'' Under a new emergency
law approved by the National Assembly on Wednesday, the president
can shut down print and broadcast media for ``the maintenance of
public order,'' but La Prensa was not ordered to close.
   The ministry notice said La Prensa ``insists in its defamatory
campaign of portraying the government of Nicaragua as responsible
for criminal events.'' It accused La Prensa of depicting the
government as generating ``a climate of threats against all persons
and organizations that say something against the Sandinista party.''
   In its Thursday editorial titled, ``An unjust order without
right and without reason,'' La Prensa said the government protests
were ``two precipitous documents ... that, lamentably, once again
incorrectly cite the country's laws and once again display an
ignorance of the legal norms that apply to the exercise of freedom
of expression in Nicaragua.''
   La Prensa also said that ``it is obvious that in recent days,
gangs of uniformed men with weapons only the army has have
committed brutal crimes that, inevitably, show common or similar
elements.''
   On Tuesday, La Prensa reported three activists with the
Confederation of Trade Union Unity were fatally shot Sunday by
three men wearing Sandinista army uniforms in Leon, about 45 miles
west of Managua. The report said the assailants used Soviet-made
AK-47 rifles, standard issue in the Sandinista army.
   La Prensa identified the slain activists as Fernando Torres,
Alejandro Peralta and Norberto Espinoza. It attributed its
information to Alvin Guthrie Rivers, secretary-general of the
anti-government confederation.
   On Wednesday, the Interior Ministry said Espinoza was a
Sandinista army first lieutenant and that Torres was a former
member of the Sandinista Police. It described Sunday's episode as a
common crime.
</TEXT>
