<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 0118EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis     10-08 0760</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Strikes Theme of Economic Nationalism</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis is hammering the Republicans on a
theme of economic nationalism, saying George Bush hung a ``do not
disturb sign'' on his door while foreign competitors and investors
battered and bought U.S. industries.
   The Democratic presidential nominee was campaigning back in his
native New England today, visiting Bates College in Lewiston,
Maine, on a sentimental stop at the place where his parents
attended college only a few years after emigrating from Greece.
   The trip to Maine, capping a campaign week highlighted by his
running mate Lloyd Bentsen's debate with Dan Quayle, was bringing
Dukakis to a small state but one the campaign hopes to carry on
Nov. 8 _ despite Bush's summer mansion on the coast at
Kennebunkport.
   ``We want to carry all of George Bush's home states,'' quipped
press secretary Dayton Duncan in a remark lampooning the vice
president's loose ties to several states.
   The Massachusetts governor returned to Boston late Friday after
campaigning in Missouri and North Carolina, assailing the Reagan
administration's record on foreign trade and Quayle's debate remark
praising foreign investment in U.S. companies for creating jobs.
   But the campaign was embarrassed to learn that the Moog
Automotive Co. in Wellston, Mo., where Dukakis delivered a speech
blasting the Republicans on the foreign investment issue, was
actually owned by an Italian auto-making conglomerate through a
U.S. holding company. And the company was bought out 11 years ago,
during a Democratic administration.
   Duncan said some in the campaign knew of its ownership, but top
campaign officials did not know and neither did Rep. Richard
Gephardt, D-Mo., who accompanied Dukakis to the plant. Dukakis's
blasts at foreign ownership set off murmers among workers at the
plant, and aides acknowledged Dukakis was unaware of the ownership
when he praised the company and its workers as ``survivors'' in the
fight for American businesses and products.
   ``If anyone asks you what's at stake in this election, just
remind them of that moment in the debate Wednesday night when Dan
Quayle said he's happy that foreign owners are buying up America,''
Dukakis said.
   ``Maybe the Republican ticket wants our children to work for
foreign owners, pay rent to foreign owners, and owe their future to
foreign owners, but that's not the kind of future Lloyd Bentsen and
I and Dick Gephardt and all of you want for America,'' he said.
   Dukakis said Bush ``has spent the last eight years with a `do
not disturb' sign hanging on his office door,'' ignoring the trade
issue.
   He said the United States enjoyed a trade surplus of $7 billion
in 1981, when the Reagan administration took over, and that by 1987
the nation suffered a trade deficit of $154 billion.
   In the debate, Quayle said: ``I would rather have people come
over here and to make investments in this country, rather than
going elsewhere. Because by coming over here, and making
investments in this country, we are seeing jobs.''
   Dukakis borrowed some of the rhetoric of former rivals Gephardt
and Jesse Jackson from the Democratic primaries as he lamented the
decline of the United States as the leading manufacturer of
consumer electronics such as color televisons, video cassette
recorders and telephones.
   Dukakis and Bentsen are calling for a new trade policy that they
say will require reciprocity, or prohibiting foreign companies from
flooding the United States with products when U.S. manufacturers
are locked out of those countries. They also support limited
restrictions on imports of some foreign products, including
textiles, so long as U.S. companies respond by modernizing to
become competitive.
   Before heading home, Dukakis stopped in Ashville, N.C., and
spoke to a crowd of 2,000 people jammed around the home of the late
author Thomas Wolfe. Now restored, the two-story white frame house
with stained glass windows, which was Wolfe's mother's boarding
house that he recalled in the book ``Look Homeward Angel,'' served
as Dukakis' backdrop and he recalled traveling to North Carolina in
1960, fresh out of law school, just to visit the house.
   Dukakis cited a Wolfe quotation that approximated the
candidate's own often-repeated theme _ that ``the best America is
yet to come'' _ and declared the two debates between the Democratic
and Republican tickets have changed the complexion of the race.
   ``I think some things happened on that stage, and some things
happened around the country ... that have made this a brand new
campaign,'' he said. ``We're starting to move folks. You can feel
it.''
</TEXT>
