<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Norelco-Filter     10-08 0312</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Norelco-Filter,0319</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Water Purifier Added Chemical As it Filtered, FTC Judge Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An administrative judge has ruled that a company
falsely advertised a water purifying device by failing to disclose
it added a probable carcinogen to the water it filtered, a
newspaper reported today.
   Last month's ruling by James P. Timothy of the Federal Trade
Commission said North American Philips Corp. of New York showed
``utter disregard for the welfare of its consumers and blatant
disregard for the law'' in marketing its Norelco Clean Water
Machine, according to The New York Times.
   The FTC had filed an administrative complaint against the
company in August 1987. The complaint said that while ads for the
machine claimed the product made tap water clean or cleaner, they
failed to disclose that filters formerly used in the product
actually added a potentially hazardous chemical to the water.
   The filters, which the company recalled in 1986, added the
chemical methylene chloride to the water that passed through them,
the complaint said. The chemical, used as a solvent in glues,
paints and other substances, has been shown to cause cancer in
laboratory animals, according to the Consumer Product Safety
Commission.
   The company sold 186,000 of the filters between 1982 and the
start of the recall in 1986, the Times reported.
   The company said distributing the tainted filters was a
management mistake, and that it would not appeal the judge's
decision, which would become final after review by the five-member
commission, according to the newspaper.
   ``We have never had that kind of accident in our 50 years of
business in North America, and we feel it has reflected too
negatively on our corporation,'' said Winfried C. van't Hoff,
Norelco executive vice president.
   ``Many of the people involved with this thing are no longer with
the company,'' said Samuel J. Rozen, the company's general counsel.
</TEXT>
