<1ST_LINE>r w PM-MedicalWaste     10-08 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Medical Waste,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Medical Waste Bill, Sends It Back to House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation to combat midnight dumping of
medical wastes has won Senate approval and now goes back to the
House for further action next week.
   The bill, which was passed in the Senate by voice vote Friday
night, sets up a system to track infectious waste like that which
fouled Atlantic beaches last summer.
   The House approved a similar bill on Thursday, but now the two
pieces of legislation must be reconciled before moving toward final
congressional approval.
   ``Spending a day at the beach shouldn't have to be followed by a
day at the doctor,'' said Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., a sponsor
of the bill.
   Senate approval came after several minor changes were made in a
version that had been passed by the House, requiring it to be
reconsidered by the House next week.
   The legislation was prompted by the waves of used syringes,
vials of AIDS-infected blood and other hospital waste that washed
up on beaches along the East Coast, Lake Michigan and Lake Erie
during the summer. The waste became a health problem, closing some
beaches because of the threat of hepatitis and other diseases.
   The bill would require the Environmental Protection Agency to
set up a system to track dangerous waste from hospitals, labs and
clinics to its disposal. Initially, the program would cover just 10
states: Connecticut, New Jersey, New York, Pennsylvania, Ohio,
Indiana, Illinois, Michigan, Wisconsin and Minnesota.
   Later, the program could be made national in scope if other
states petition to subject their medical waste to the same
cradle-to-grave monitoring system for medical supplies.
   Included in the paper-trail tracking system would be blood,
hypodermic needles, scalpels and surgical and laboratory waste that
has been in contact with infectious agents. They would have to be
segregated from other medical waste and tracked to make sure they
reached a proper disposal facility.
   The problem has received substantial publicity this year after
fouled stretches of beach in New York and New Jersey were closed,
ruining vacations and causing lost revenues for oceanside
businesses and resorts.
   Lautenberg said the waste problem appears to be the result of
illegal dumpers who ``threaten the well-being of their fellow
citizens to save a few dollars in disposal costs.''
   Lawmakers criticized the EPA, which they said has had authority
to regulate the wastes but has ignored the problem.
</TEXT>
