<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FDA-Toothpaste     10-08 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-FDA-Toothpaste,190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FDA Cites Violations By Makers of Toothpaste, Mouthwash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has accused six toothpaste and
mouthwash producers of violating the law by claiming their products
can prevent plaque or gum disease, according to a published report.
   In letters to the companies last July, the Food and Drug
Administration instructed them to stop making the claims or provide
supporting evidence, The Washington Post reported in today's
editions.
   The Post identified the companies and their products as:
Warner-Lambert, Listerine mouthwash; Colgate-Palmolive, Colgate
toothpaste; Beecham Products, Aquafresh toothpaste; Vipont Inc.,
Viadent oral rinse; Oral Research Laboratories, Plax dental rinse;
and Rydelle-Lion Inc., Checkup toothpaste.
   FDA spokeswoman Faye Peterson said other companies had agreed
voluntarily to change their labeling.
   In its letters, the FDA said the companies had not submitted
evidence proving that toothpaste or mouthwash is safe or effective
for dealing with plaque or gingivitis.
   ``We are not aware of any evidence establishing that the product
is generally recognized as safe and effective for gingivitis,'' the
letters said.
   The FDA added that if no evidence was forthcoming, the product
is considered as being ``marketed in violation of the Federal Food,
Drug and Cosmetic Act and at risk of regulatory action.''
   The letters were sent by Rudolf Apodaca, director of the
division of labeling compliance at FDA.
</TEXT>
