<DOCNO> AP881008-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 0148EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Wallace-Westmoreland     10-08 0197</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wallace-Westmoreland,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wallace Says He Softened His Style After Libel Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS News correspondent Mike Wallace says the
``sobering'' experience of the 18-week Westmoreland libel trial 3{
years ago led him to tone down his aggressive interviewing style.
   ``You learn how it feels to be the object of the press's
scrutiny,'' Wallace said in an interview appearing in Sunday's
Parade magazine. ``I learned how it must feel for someone I am
covering to believe he is being treated unfairly. That gave me
sobering second thoughts.''
   Gen. William Westmoreland filed a $120 million libel suit
against Wallace and CBS for a 1982 ``60 Minutes'' piece narrated by
Wallace that claimed Westmoreland deceived the American public
about enemy troop strength during the Vietnam War. Westmoreland
dropped the charges in February 1985 before the case went to a jury.
   Wallace said he is less interested now in riling an interviewee
to produce dramatic television.
   ``I used to say I was after light, not heat. But the fact
remained that the heat, more than the light, generated the
attention I got,'' Wallace said. ``Then you grow, you understand
more. Over the years, light has taken precedence.''
</TEXT>
