<HEAD>Five Girls Killed By Speeding Car</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS name to Weitzel sted Weitezel throughout.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PULASKI, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A speeding car hit a utility pole Friday
night and careened into a group of five girls on a sidewalk,
killing all of them, authorities said.
   The car hit a tree after striking the girls, said Brown County
Sheriff's Lt. George Weitzel. He said the driver of the car, who a
school principal said was a teen-ager, and his sister were taken to
hospitals and were believed to be in serious condition.
   Four of the girls were dead at the scene and a fifth was
pronounced dead at a hospital, Weitzel said. All were elementary
school students and believed to be between ages 12 and 14.
   The accident occurred at 6:49 p.m. in Pulaski, a village of
1,875 located about 15 miles northwest of Green Bay in northeastern
Wisconsin.
   ``The entire community is in a state of shock,'' said Pulaksi
High School Principal Guy David. He said the driver of the car was
a 16-year-old student at the high school.
   The victims' identities were not immediately available pending
notification of relatives.
   ``We heard they (the girls) were coming from a birthday party or
slumber party, either coming or going. All were on the sidewalk
when it happened,'' Weitzel said.
   ``We got one vehicle with a brother and sister evidently driving
at a high rate of speed. The vehicle hits a power pole, strikes
five girls _ four dead at the scene and one dies at a hospital _
and then the car hit a tree,'' he said.
   David said the five girls were all students at Glenbrook
Elementary School. The children were walking near the village post
office and police station when they were struck, he said.
   ``This is going to be a real problem for the community to deal
with. It will be very difficult,'' he said. ``In a small community
like this, everybody knows everybody.''
   Saturday's high school football game was canceled because of the
tragedy, the principal said.
</TEXT>
