<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0446,0607</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protests Spread In Yugoslavia; Party Promises Changes</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with three grafs to CORRECT spelling of Vojvodina in
3rd graf; picks up 4th pvs: More than...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of demonstrators
nationwide marched on goverment buildings and demanded an overhaul
in the communist hierarchy in a spreading wave of ethnic and
economic unrest.
   National Communist Party leaders, trying to control the strife,
promised urgent personnel changes and economic reforms later this
month.
   The protests Friday came just one day after 30,000 people
surrounded a government building in the province of Vojvodina,
battling police and eventually forcing the resignations of the
15-member provincial Politburo.
   More than 10,000 people, some chanting ``You betrayed us,''
staged a similar rally in Titograd on Friday in the republic of
Montenegro, demanding the immediate ouster of the local communist
party leadership.
   The rally in front of the Montenegrin Parliament building was
triggered by a strike of about 1,000 construction firm workers who
put down their tools earlier Friday to protest low wages and
falling living standards, state-run media reports said.
   Several similar protests, triggered by the country's worst
economic and social crisis in history, were staged Friday in
eastern and southern parts of the country.
   Meanwhile, the ruling national Communist presidium issued a
statement saying the policy-making Central Committee plenum to meet
Oct. 17 ``will make necessary personnel changes in the presidium,
which should contribute to the more efficient work of the organ.''
   There have been increasing calls in Yugoslavia for top-level
personnel changes as the unrest continues. The public protests stem
from a general dissatisfaction with a crippled economy and
long-simmering fueds between ethnic groups.
   Communist leaders have been blamed for failing to defuse
tensions between the mostly Christian Slav minority and the largely
Moslem ethnic Albanian majority in the southern Kosovo province _ a
hotbed of unrest _ in the republic of Serbia.
   In Belgrade, 400 high school students from Kosovo marched Friday
on the national Parliament, chanting that Serbs will never give up
power in Kosovo, an autonomous province bordering Albania, Belgrade
radio reported.
   Serbs, who are mainly Christian, charge that persecution by
Kosovo's ethnic Albanians is forcing them to emigrate. Mostly
Moslem ethnic Albanians make up 90 percent of the province's
population.
   In Krusevac, 90 miles south of Belgrade, several thousand
workers demonstrated Friday to demand higher wages and the ouster
of Communist leaders, the radio said.
   The presidium statement appealed for urgent changes in the
country's political and economic system to help in resolving the
current crisis, which includes growing labor unrest, a 217 percent
annual inflation and a $21 billion foreign debt.
   In a recent interview, Yugoslav Premier Branko Mikulic said the
country ``will introduce a completly new market-oriented economic
system as of 1989.'' Currently, Yugoslavia's economy is a mixture
of Western-style free market system and Soviet-style central
planning.
   Nearly 100 people, including 14 policemen, were injured in
Thursday's rioting in Vojvodina, in the city of Novi Sad.
Demonstrators hurled rocks and bottles at police.
   The protest eventually caused the mass resignation of the
Vojvodina leadership, which was considered a major victory for the
Serbian communist boss Slobodan Milosevic.
   Milosevic, hailed by his supporters as political heir to the
late President Josip Broz Tito, has been demanding more central
control for his republic over its two provinces, Kosovo and
Vojvodina. Kosovo and Vojvodina are the country's only two
autonomous provinces.
   Thursday's shake-up in Vojvodina has prompted speculation that
Kosovo party leaders could also be on their way out too.
</TEXT>
