<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     10-08 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CRAB ORCHARD, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When it comes to forecasting the
weather, just give Helen Lane a woolly worm and a corn husk.
   ``I think it'll get a little warmer before it gets cold again,
and give us some real nice days in November,'' was her
pronouncement this week on Helen Lane Day in Crab Orchard, a town
60 miles west of Knoxville.
   The 68-year-old prognosticator, considered generally accurate
for the past 29 years, predicted two heavy snowfalls for the coming
winter.
   Mrs. Lane has been making predictions since 1959, when her
warnings of a harsh winter were followed by 28 storms and more than
6 feet of snow.
   ``Don't Say You Weren't Warned'' was the headline in the
Crossville Chronicle, which published her predictions that autumn.
   People have paid attention to her assessment of woolly worms,
corn husks and the number of dense August fogs ever since. The
darker the woolly worms and the thicker the husks, the more severe
the winter will be, she says.
   This will be a generally cold, dry winter, she said Thursday.
There could be more snow than the two storms, she said, but it
won't amount to much.
   Mrs. Lane learned her methods from her father, who in turn
absorbed the lessons handed down from previous generations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOUNTAIN CENTER, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The biggest fish story of the
week to come out of Lake Hemet lost some of its teeth when a
fisherman's catch turned out to be a vegetarian pacu instead of a
flesh-eating piranha.
   The unusual fish was hooked by a Fullerton man Monday and rumors
quickly spread that the perch-shaped creature with lots of teeth
was a piranha.
   ``I called a state biologist because I'd never seen a piranha,''
other than in books and movies, said Chief Ranger Jim Henry of the
Lake Hemet Municipal Water District.
   Henry froze the fish for examination by biologist Frank Hoover.
   The report that came back Wednesday from the state Department of
Fish and Game said the fish was actually a pacu, a vegetable-eating
creature in the same family as the piranha. A native of South
America, the pacu probably wouldn't have survived the winter in the
lake in the San Jacinto Mountains, about 50 miles east of Los
Angeles.
   Henry also went back to the small lake Thursday to squelch the
rumors among the lake's fishermen.
   State law prohibits importation or possession of piranha but it
doesn't apply to the pacu.
   ``I think somebody is just letting them loose, kind of like
people who start forest fires to sit back and watch,'' Hoover said.
</TEXT>
