<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PeshtigoFire Bjt   10-08 0647</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Peshtigo Fire, Bjt,0666</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Few Know About North America's Deadliest Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PESHTIGO, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most Peshtigo Fire Museum visitors never
heard of North America's deadliest fire, which erupted 117 years
ago today and killed 1,150 people but was overshadowed by the
famous Chicago conflagration.
   ``A lot of tourists go through here, and it surprises me most
people are unaware of the tragedy,'' said Stella Van Bogart, a
museum curator. ``The museum's been open 25 years and this still
goes on.''
   ``It's something that people around here remember. It's taught
in elementary school classes,'' said Peshtigo School Superintendent
George Fox.
   Still, even in this northeast Wisconsin community of about
3,000, the anniversary will go unmarked.
   The small museum, housed in a church built after the blaze, has
only a tabernacle and a few charred pieces of wood to memorialize
the inferno. Next to the church is a graveyard where a stone marks
a mass grave for about 350 unidentified victims.
   Ed Kautz of the U.S. Forest Service said the Peshtigo fire
remains the blaze with the highest known death toll on the
continent. It also is the world's second-deadliest blaze, surpassed
only by an 1845 fire at a theater in Canton, China, killing 1,670,
according to The World Almanac.
   The fire helped spur the development of many firefighting and
conservation techniques still used today, said Kautz and state
forest firefighting specialists.
   Fueled and spread by a tornado, the inferno killed at least
1,150 people, burned about 1.28 million acres of pine forest in
eight counties and caused $5 million in damage, not counting lost
timber.
   But the fire that destroyed Peshtigo, which took 30 years to
rebuild, has become a footnote in history to a smaller fire. On the
same day, Oct. 8, 1871, the famous Chicago fire erupted. It killed
250 people during its four-day rampage.
   A drought parched northeastern Wisconsin most of the summer and
fall of 1871. Despite that, loggers continued to clear the land,
leaving slash and other debris in continuously burning piles.
   Railroad workers extending track and farmers clearing land also
piled or burned debris for acres.
   As many townspeople were returning from an evening church
service or eating supper, the fire began.
   Historian Stewart H. Holbrook wrote: ``A southwest wind blew
flurries of white ashes on the town like a snowstorm. Then
townspeople heard what sounded like the rumble of a train and then
a roar as the fiery tornado descended on it.''
   Pine sidewalks and houses were ablaze when a rush of gale-force
wind sent sheets of fire onto the town from the red, glowing sky.
   The tornado-swept fire was preceded by blinding smoke. About 300
people were killed on a wooden bridge after they ran onto it to
flee the blaze, but it collapsed and burned. Some were wedged
between the burning logs in the water.
   The intense wind blew fire like a blow torch from the banks to
burn the heads of people who sought safety in neck-deep Peshtigo
River.
   So many people were burned to ashes that teeth often were the
only way to distinguish animals from man, survivors said.
   Others were killed by the tornado, suffocated after seeking
refuge in wells, or were trampled by terrified cattle.
   In one case, a father slit the throats of his four children and
wife and then himself to spare them a burning death.
   Historical accounts indicated the fire lasted an hour in
Peshtigo, from 9 p.m. to 10 p.m., before moving on to other
villages. Historians estimate that about 800 of Peshtigo's 1,700
residents were killed and at least 350 in the other communities
died. About 1,500 people were badly injured and 3,000 were left
homeless.
   No one knew of the Peshtigo fire for days because telegraph
poles had burned down almost a month earlier in other small brush
fires. Help did not reach victims for several days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
