<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Poland-Rally     10-08 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Poland-Rally,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Break Up Protest Staged By Dissidents</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto NY-8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police in jeeps and trucks broke up a
gathering of 2,000 people when a satiric dissident group tried to
hold a demonstration ``to defend communism'' at a monument to the
founder of the Soviet secret police.
   About 50 people were arrested Friday by uniformed and
plainclothed police, who started seizing demonstrators and checking
their identity papers even before the rally was to begin at 3 p.m.
at a busy central plaza.
   The rally was organized by the Orange Alternative, a movement
which has gained popularity among young people in recent years with
its ``happenings'' that poke fun at authorities. The movement is
based in the southwestern city of Wroclaw.
   ``You have two minutes to disperse. No jokes any more. Go
home,'' police said over loudspeakers before driving jeeps and
trucks through the crowd huddled along sidewalks accross from the
busy square. Demonstrators chanted ``KGB'' and ``Solidarity.''
   Scuffles broke out as police chased demonstrators who darted in
front of oncoming trams and rush-hour traffic to avoid detention.
Demonstrators blew plastic whistles and jeered at the police, who
formed cordons and shoved the crowd into adjacent side streets.
   One policeman bloodied his face after tripping on the pavement
while chasing a fleeing youth. Police refrained from using their
truncheons, but tried to control the size of the crowd by refusing
to let people get out of arriving trams.
   Protesters took shelter after the police moved in, rushing away
from the oncoming police vehicles into shops adjoining the plaza,
and a minor brawl erupted in one shoestore when officers tried to
seize a banner carried by three youths.
   Some demonstrators, including women and old people, were roughed
up or pulled by the hair while being detained.
   It took the police more than two hours to clear the square.
   The rally was held at Dzierzynski Square, named after Feliks
Dzierzynski, a Polish supporter of the Bolshevik Revolution who in
1918 founded the Cheka, the secret police organization that was the
forerunner of today's KGB.
   The protest coincided with the officially proclaimed
``Policeman's Day'' in Poland. Earlier in the day, a police
delegation placed flowers and Polish flags at the bottom of the
monument.
   Organizers had put up colorful orange-lettered posters at Warsaw
University and distributed leaflets throughout the city announcing
the rally. Police began patrolling the square early Friday morning.
   A spokesman for the Independent Student Association, known by
its Polish initials NZS, said police detained five people Thursday
night in advance of the rally and four others received telephone
warnings not to participate.
   In June, about 1,000 Orange Alternative supporters held mock
elections and lampooned various government officials in Warsaw on
the day of nationwide municipal elections. Police did not interfere.
</TEXT>
