<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Fashion     10-08 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Fashion,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Fashion Opens In Burst of Color, Looking East</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EDITH M. LEDERER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British Designer Show opened with a burst of
color, a breath of Eastern adventure and a boost from Prime
Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   If the 300 designers exhibiting at the four-day show have their
way, next summer's look will be soft, shapely, leggy and exotic
with a bit of the zany eccentricity that has become a British
fashion hallmark.
   ``It's going to be brights and colors,'' said designer Benny
Ong. ``I think women have now come to realize that color is no
longer an apology for being themselves. It's like a coming out
party for women ... so, long live color!''
   Added David Sassoon, who designs for most of the British royals:
``I think it's a softer, more fluid look -- away from the
constructed dresses of last season.''
   Sandwiched between the Milan and Paris shows, London has become
an important stopping off point for buyers in the last five years,
especially those looking for something different. Organizers expect
6,000 buyers by the tie the show, which opened Friday, concludes on
Monday.
   ``France is a wonderful seduction. Italy is healthy and always
good and England is more of the adventure and the whimsy,'' said
Bernie Ozer, vice president of New York's Associated Merchandising
Corp., the world's largest international marketing and buying
service whose clients range from Harrods to Bloomingdales.
   The London fashion showcase has been a crucial selling platform
for the British clothing industry, whose exports increased from
$1.7 billion in 1984 to $2.43 billion in 1987.
   Mrs. Thatcher, an avid backer of British trade, held a reception
for top designers and buyers at her official 10 Downing St.
residence Friday night _ the social highlight of the London shows.
   She presented the British Fashion Council's Designer of the Year
award to Turkish-born Rifat Ozbek, whose powerful figure-hugging
clothes have won international acclaim since he started his own
label four years ago.
   Though Ozbek is not showing his summer collection until Monday,
a sneak preview revealed a distinct Middle Eastern feel in his
prints mixed with kaftan-stitched linens and striped pyjamas.
   But the London message seems to be coming from further east, in
Malaysia, Singapore and India: the sarong is the skirt for summer
and there are several filmy sari-like shawls and wraps.
   Betty Jackson used the atmosphere of Indonesia for her printed
and sequinned sarong skirts. Edina Ronay, who designs for the
Duchess of York, also featured sarongs, and Arabella Pollen, a
favorite of Princess Diana, used the sarong as the main skirt for
her collection.
   ``It's a sort of fake sarong,'' Ms. Pollen said. ``It's a nice
safe sarong. It actually fits quite nicely in the back and the
sarong is an extra piece. I hate those sarongs where when you shift
your leg the whole thing moves.''
   Washed silks from the East were also popular with Betty Jackson,
Arabella Pollen and Workers for Freedom, one of London's young
design teams. They featured a ``Summer Eskimos'' collection of
burnt orange and indigo tie-dye washable silk off-one-shoulder
tunics teamed with sequinned lace long skirts or pants.
   At the top end of the market, where eccentricity rarely reaches,
there was concern that the American buyers might continue to stay
away because of the strong pound and weak dollar _ and about the
state of the industry as a whole.
</TEXT>
