<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Shoreham     10-08 0331</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Shoreham,1st Ld Writethru,a0457,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NRC Panel Overturns Decision Allowing Shoreham License</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Following SUBs 1st graf clarifying location of plant and
conforming to style.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owner of the idled Shoreham nuclear power
plant on New York's Long Island has vowed to fight an appeals board
ruling taking away authorization for the plant to receive a
full-power operating license.
   ``We will appeal (the) decision directly to the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission,'' Jim Lois, a spokesman for Long Island
Lighting Co., said Friday.
   Lois was reacting to a ruling Friday by a three-judge panel of
the Atomic Safety and Licensing Appeals Board that a licensing
panel did not have the authority to remove state and local
governments as intevenors in the case.
   As a result, the appeals board said, all outstanding emergency
planning issues had not been resolved in the Shoreham case and the
basis for the full-power license authorization ``does not exist.''
   On Sept. 23, a three-judge panel of the Atomic Safety and
Licensing Board threw out New York state, Suffolk County and the
Town of Southampton as intervenors in a case involving an emergency
evacuation drill conducted at Shoreham. The panel also found that
there was reasonable assurance that the public's safety could be
protected in the event of an accident at the reactor.
   Both the appeal board and the licensing panel are part of the
Nuclear Regulatory Commission.
   State and local authorities have refused to participate in
emergency planning at the reactor, which has been completed since
1984 but has never operated. They maintain that Long Island could
not be safely evacuated in an emergency.
   Current federal regulation prevents the NRC from issuing a
full-power license to a nuclear plant unless there is an emergency
plan that gives reaasonable assurance the public will be safe if an
accident occurs.
   Francis Sheehan, a spokesman for New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, said
the governor had no immediate comment on the court decision.
</TEXT>
