<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WNBCGoodbye     10-08 0675</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-WNBC Goodbye,0696</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Radio City Without Radio: WNBC Signs Off After 62 Years On The Air</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY24</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH MENDELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radio City no longer has a radio station.
   With tears, memories, and voices from the past, WNBC went off
the air Friday after 62 years of broadcasting that included the
first commercial, the comedy of Jack Benny and Bob Hope, and the
conducting of Arturo Toscanini.
   ``We have a very big supply of tissues here at the studio,''
said Alan Colmes, host of the last radio show from the NBC studios
in Rockefeller Center, which inspired the name of the neighboring
Radio City Music Hall. A sports-talk station took over the 660 spot
on the AM dial.
   ``It's historic, but sad,'' Colmes said. ``There is something
about this building, maybe a radio muse that makes everything so
special. The list of people who have been fired from this station
is a who's who of radio.''
   At the end of Friday's show, everyone in the studio counted down
from 10, but the power was turned off before NBC's distinctive
three-gong chime could sound for the last time. The switch was
thrown at 5:30 p.m. and WFAN signed on.
   The new station, which has its studios in Queens, takes over a
50,000-watt, clear-channel signal that can be picked up in as many
as 35 states at night.
   Colmes began the last show routinely, by reading a mattress
commercial, and got an unexpected laugh.
   ``And for a limited time, just mention WNBC and you'll get a
free mattress cover. Make that very limited,'' Colmes cracked.
   While there were a lot of laughs, it was a bittersweet show,
featuring visits and telephone calls from some famous WNBC veterans
and well-wishers, including Bill Cullen, Ed McMahon, Joyce
Brothers, ``Cousin'' Bruce Morrow, Alan King, Marv Albert, Gabe
Pressman and Ted Brown.
   The demise of WNBC, announced earlier this year, is the result
of the $6 billion deal in 1985 in which General Electric Co. bought
RCA Corp., the parent company of NBC.
   Federal Communications Commission rules prevent a new owner from
keeping both a television and radio station in the same market, so
GE decided to sell its newly acquired radio properties and keep the
more profitable WNBC-TV.
   The changes, announced Feb. 18, mean about 50 WNBC employees are
out of work.
   The NBC radio network went to Westwood One for $55 million. Five
local stations _ including WNBC and WYNY-FM in New York _ brought
$121 million from Emmis Broadcasting Corp. GE has one station left,
KNBR in San Francisco, which is for sale.
   Emmis' WFAN, which had been at 1050 on the dial, features
play-by-play of Mets baseball games and other sports events.
   WNBC began its farewell broadcast with a taped 90-minute survey
of the station's history.
   The station went on the air in April 1922 as an AT&T experiment
that settled on the call letters WEAF five months later.
   In 1926, the Radio Corp. of America and its NBC network, created
to help sell the radios it was producing, bought WEAF for $1
million. The station's call letters were changed to WNBC in 1946,
changed again in 1954 to WRCA, then reverted to WNBC in 1960.
   Many firsts attributed to NBC's forerunner, WEAF, include: the
first World Series broadcast, 1923; the first coast-to-coast
hookup, 1924; and the first broadcast of national political
conventions, 1924.
   The first radio commercial was aired on WEAF on Aug. 28, 1922,
when a real estate developer paid $100 for a 10-minute sales pitch
for apartments.
   Friday's show included clips from programs featuring Hope,
Benny, Fred Allen, George and Gracie Allen, and the NBC Symphony
conducted by Toscanini.
   Other NBC classics also were showcased: ``Amos 'n' Andy,''
``Doctor IQ,'' ``You Bet Your Life'' with Groucho Marx, ``The Big
Show'' and ``Monitor.''
   In the early 1960s, as television became the showplace for the
stars, the station dropped soap operas, mysteries, quiz shows and
live big band performances and began broadcasting news, call-in
programs and music shows.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881008-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 0530EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TeenResearcher     10-08 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teen Researcher,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Whiz Kid Delivers Paper On Colon Cancer</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY12</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fourteen-year-old Ray Bateman Jr. is almost a
typical American teen-ager. Except for his preoccupation with
finding a cure for colon cancer.
   Ray collaborated with cancer researcher Dr. Glen Tisman and
delivered their test results Friday to the American Federation for
Clinical Research.
   ``Ray has tremendous scientific gifts that come naturally,''
Tisman said after watching the teen-ager deliver the slide show and
speech in a steady, if squeaky, voice.
   ``This started as a school project, but obviously got much
bigger,'' said Ray, flashing a brace-bedecked smile after the
presentation.
   The Huntington Beach, Calif., computer whiz received two rounds
of applause from a group of two dozen researchers.
   ``I think it was very exciting,'' said Dr. Mark Moskowitz of
Newton, Mass., who attended the presentation. ``We need more young
investigators. ... He could be the first of a new generation of
medical researchers.''
   Ray was accompanied to the convention by his parents and Tisman.
The pair worked together on a plan to combine a chemical,
5-Fluorodeoxyuridine _ 5FUdR for short _ with a vitamin derivative
in an effort to kill cancer cells, the teen-ager said.
   Both agreed the plan needed additional testing, although initial
indicators showed it had potential in fighting cancer.
   Ray delivered the research because the research federation's
rules state that if two authors submit a paper and one is older
than 41, the younger one must make the presentation. Tisman is 46;
he recruited Ray to assist in doing computer analyses of his
research.
   ``What Ray has done here is make the whole thing possible,''
Tisman said.
   Ray, who spent an estimated 1,300 hours on the research, said he
hoped to continue work on the therapy and start a career in
medicine. The teen-ager's parents say they have spent $25,000 on
computers.
   ``I would like to be involved in something both research and
clinical,'' Ray said. ``I don't think it would be all that much fun
to do research and not see it applied.''
</TEXT>
