<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 0557EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Brawley     10-08 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brawley,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brawley Grand Jurors Speak Out; Girl's Advisers To Confer with
Farrakhan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Contents of 11th graf may offend some readers.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of the grand jury that
rejected Tawana Brawley's story of abduction and rape by a gang of
whites said no evidence whatsoever supported the black teen-ager's
tale.
   ``This thing wasn't a mere preponderance of evidence,'' said
Anthony Montanari. ``It was all the evidence that pointed to the
conclusion that we drew.''
   But Jimmy Powell, one of two black members of the 23-member
grand jury that disbanded Friday after probing the case since Feb.
29, said he was unconvinced the 16-year-old was lying. He said he
opposed the vote to accept the 170-page report.
   ``The evidence wasn't there to support the conclusion,'' Powell
said Friday.
   He said he wasn't the only grand juror to disagree with the
report, but wouldn't give any more details about the deliberations.
   The report flatly stated Miss Brawley had not been sexually
assaulted. It said all evidence suggested that the teen-ager, found
last Nov. 28 with racial epithets and dog feces smeared on her
body, had inflicted the condition on herself.
   Miss Brawley, who said she was abducted for four days, was found
in a garbage bag outside her family's former apartment in
Wappingers Falls, 75 miles north of New York City.
   State Supreme Court Judge Angelo Ingrassia, who ordered the
report released to the public, said the grand jury's conclusions
``were beyond a reasonable doubt.''
   Timothy Gilles, spokesman for Attorney General Robert Abrams,
said Abrams wouldn't comment on the grand jury deliberations. Grand
jury reports do not have to be unanimous. The New York Daily News
reported the vote was 22-1.
   Montanari refused to discuss the panel's final vote, saying he
feared he'd be guilty of a crime.
   Montanari said evidence linking charred cloth used to scrawl the
slurs ``KKK'' and ``nigger'' on the girl's body to fibers found
under Miss Brawley's fingernails proved to be crucial in clinching
the case.
   ``That was very, very revealing,'' he said.
   But he said that testimony from Miss Brawley, who refused to
cooperate with the grand jury on the advice of her advisers, would
have made a difference.
   ``There's only one person who's sure to know what happened to
Tawana Brawley and that's Tawana Brawley,'' Montanari said.
   The other black grand juror, George Pelote, who voted to approve
the report, told the Daily News, ``We all felt something did happen
to her, but not what was claimed by her.''
   In Chicago, the Rev. Al Sharpton, one of Miss Brawley's three
advisers, said the girl would appear at a news conference over the
weekend to discuss ``the substance of the grand jury findings.''
   ``We have information and evidence that is going to rock the
world,'' said Sharpton.
   He said the Brawley family, which now lives in Virginia Beach,
Va., had been invited to attend the Chicago convention three months
ago by Nation of Islam leader Louis Farrakhan.
   ``We want to sit down with Minister Farrakhan ... to go over
several of the contradictions in the report ... and make a very
itemized analysis of it,'' Sharpton said.
</TEXT>
