<2ND_LINE>PM-Hostage's Sister,0318</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sister Hopeful Anderson Will Be Released By Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hostages</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBBIE NEWBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sister of the longest-held hostage in
Lebanon, journalist Terry Anderson, said it will be ``very
devastating'' to her brother if he is not released by the Nov. 8
presidential election.
   ``Terry is geared to the elections,'' Peggy Say said Friday,
based on the word she received from a recently freed hostage.
   ``He feels it will take that to get him out of there. I'm afraid
if they come and go, it's going to be very devastating to him.''
   The last word on Anderson's condition came from Marcel Fontaine,
a French hostage released in May, said Mrs. Say, who lives in
Cadiz, Ky. Fontaine said Anderson was hanging on, with hopes of
release by the election.
   A Beirut magazine said Friday the American hostages would be
freed before the election. And an Israeli newspaper said the United
States made a deal with Iran to free the American hostages in
exchange for delivery of arms and spare parts to Iran through South
Korea. U.S. officials denied the report.
   Mrs. Say also criticized the U.S. government for refusing to
negotiate the release of her brother and the six other Americans
held by Islamic extremists in Lebanon.
   Mrs. Say told editors and publishers Friday at the fall
newspaper meeting of the Kentucky Associated Press that the United
States routinely has negotiated the release of other American
hostages in the Middle East and elsewhere.
   Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The Associated
Press, was abducted March 16, 1985. He will be 41 on Oct. 27.
   Mithileshwar Singh, a 60-year-old Indian citizen and resident
alien of the United States, was released Monday, raising hope for
the freedom of the other hostages. Mrs. Say said Singh was never in
contact with her brother.
</TEXT>
