<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 0718EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Protest     10-08 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Protest,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Drag Away Demonstrators Demanding Democracy, Let Others
Argue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities hauled away about a dozen leaders of a
group demanding democratic change during a rally that drew more
than 1,000 people to a city square.
   However, they let others in the crowd at Pushkin Square Friday
argue for hours about whether freedom and democracy really exist in
the Soviet Union.
   ``What kind of democracy is this?'' onlookers shouted at police
and paramilitary troops who elbowed and shoved their way into the
crowd. The demonstrators hoisted small signs calling for freedom
and democracy.
   Friday was Constitution Day in the Soviet Union, a national
holiday. A group called the Democratic Union mounted the protest to
demand democratic changes.
   Police hauled away a woman carrying a small child after she
briefly lifted a sign and began arguing loudly with an elderly man.
   ``We do have freedom in this country!'' the man said.
   ``Aren't you ashamed?'' she replied, gesturing at the police as
they came to take her away.
   The police moved gently for the most part, exhorting people
through megaphones to ``move on.'' After 45 minutes, when the crowd
had not responded, the demands softened to ``Please move on.''
   A police officer said through the loudspeakers repeatedly: ``The
people's deputies have ordered there will be no meeting.''
   ``What people?'' said a man in the crowd who was elegantly
dressed in a gray suit.
   At least 10 busloads of police and paramilitary troops were at
the square in central Moscow, but fewer than 100 men actually went
into the crowd.
   Arguments sprang up among bystanders, with some criticizing and
others defending the government. Whenever arguments in the square
evolved into speeches, police moved in.
   How many in the crowd supported the demonstrators became clear
when one raised a protest sign half an hour after the initial
detentions. About 50 of the more than 1,000 onlookers applauded,
but the rest merely craned their necks to read the sign.
   Stanislav Dergunov, a member of the fledgling Democratic Union,
said the group's main objective was to change Article 6 of the
constitution, which gives the Communist Party a monopoly on power.
   In the tense moments following the detentions, when no one knew
whether police would stop after taking the protest leaders,
journalists and police gathered around Nikita Kirilov.
   He carried a 1960s peace sign and a wore a handmade badge with a
drawing of barbed wire that identified him as a Democratic Union
member.
   ``I'm not holding a demonstration. I'm giving an interview,'' he
told police.
   They left him alone.
   Col. Georgy Postoyuk, the police supervisor on the scene,
finally ordered his men to back off. He denied anyone had been
arrested and declared, smiling, ``They're all here.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
