<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ToxicCloud     10-08 0232</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Toxic Cloud,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds Return To Palm Springs Homes After Cloud Passes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several hundred residents were
allowed to return home and the regional airport was reopened after
a toxic cloud that spewed from a swimming pool company dissipated,
officials said today.
   Three members of the police and fire departments were admitted
to Desert Hospital for chlorine inhalation. The incident began
about 5:30 p.m. Friday when fire broke out at the Ocean Pool Mart
and prompted evacuations in a square-mile residential area, said
police Sgt. Tom Barton.
   Fumes from chlorine, a common pool chemical, can burn skin and
eyes and cause respiratory problems.
   The injured firefighters and police officers were not seriously
hurt and were expected to be released today, Barton said.
   Several residents also complained of breathing difficulty and
eye irritation, but none was hospitalized, Barton said.
   ``I could smell the chlorine in the air. It made my nose burn
and it gave me a slight headache,'' said Hazel Reed, who is
vacationing at a condominium in the evacuated area.
   Residents were allowed to return home about 9:30 p.m., Barton
said.
   Commercial flights and the many private jets coming into Palm
Springs Regional Airport were diverted to Ontario Airport, about 50
miles to the west. Outgoing flights from this desert resort 110
miles east of Los Angeles were canceled and the airport was
evacuated, officials said.
</TEXT>
