<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Pope-France 4thLd-Writethru   10-08 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pope-France, 4th Ld - Writethru,a0493,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Takes Vision Of United Europe To France</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to UPDATE with pope's comments in speech.
Pickup 5th graf pvs, ``John Paul...'' Minor deletions to trim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STRASBOURG, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II began a four-day
visit to France today and called on Europe to unite as a continent
guided by Christian values honoring human dignity and the ideals of
liberty, tolerance and respect for law.
   Speaking in French to the 21-nation Council of Europe, the pope
said the countries of the old continent should remember their
common Christian heritage and apply it to policy governing family
life, technology, education and employment.
   ``The most urgent problem on which all nations should cooperate
is access to work,'' the pope said.
   ``Is it utopian to ask that when decisions of an economic nature
are made there should be consideration of the trials of those who
lose through unemployment a part of their dignity and sometimes
even their strength to hope?'' he asked.
   John Paul, making his fourth visit to France and his 40th
foreign trip as pope, was greeted in a light rain at
Strasbourg-Entzheim airport by President Francois Mitterrand, who
spoke in his welcoming remarks of a ``dream of a unified Europe.''
   About 150 dignitaries were joined at the airport by about 200
other people, including children who waved yellow papal pennants
and red, blue and white French flags.
   The pontiff, speaking in French, said the Roman Catholic church
views ``with satisfaction the efforts made by the European
countries to tighten still more their bonds and forge a common
future.
   ``I see it as a matter of urgency that these peoples draw from
the common wellsprings of the faith and values which are their most
precious heritage,'' he said.
   The pope's DC-9 Alitalia plane left Rome just as a strike was
getting under way at Leonardo da Vinci airport by pilots, flight
technicians and airport personnel in a dispute over reorganization
of airport management.
   In the past, the Polish-born pontiff has called on Europeans to
draw together on the basis of their common Christian heritage and
reject ``unnatural divisions'' splitting Europe into power blocs.
   John Paul, 68, was expected to expand on that theme during
speeches today to the Council of Europe and European Court of Human
Rights, and to the European Parliament on Tuesday. All three
institutions meet at the Palace of Europe in Strasbourg.
   His message comes at a time of sharp economic divisions among
the Common Market nations. The agreement by European Economic
Community members to fully integrate their economies in 1992 has
touched off widespread debate about whether Western Europe should
move toward becoming a single political unit.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher of Britain provoked protests
last month when she declared a U.S.-style European union would be
``highly damaging'' to the individual states.
   The pope's visit was timed so he could take part in the 2,000th
anniversary of Strasbourg. He also has scheduled visits to the
dioceses of Strasbourg, Metz and Nancy, all in the northeast near
West Germany.
   The Council of Europe is composed of 21 parliamentary
democracies that make up nearly all non-communist Europe. It aims
to coordinate European legislation through a series of accords and
to encourage unity, democracy and human rights.
   The 39-year-old organization has produced 110 conventions on
subjects ranging from terrorism to wildlife protection. The most
important of them is the European Convention on Human Rights.
   Unlike the European Parliament, the Council of Europe and its
judicial organs are not related to the European Economic Community,
or Common Market.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881008-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 0807EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Chile-Journalists     10-08 0348</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chile-Journalists,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foreign Journalists Say Police Assaults on Them are No Accident</HEAD>
<HEAD>with PM-Chile, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign journalists who were kicked and
clubbed by riot police while covering anti-government
demonstrations said they were intentionally attacked and filed a
complaint with the National Police.
   ``We were crouched behind a fruit stand _ not in the way and
trying to get out of the way'' Associated Press photographer John
Hopper said Friday evening after police fired water cannons and
tear gas, and then charged into a crowd of several hundred
demonstrators.
   ``We were clearly identified as press people,'' Hopper said.
``They ripped our gas masks off. I was blinded (by tear gas) and
could not see.''
   At least 12 journalists were injured Friday, including
Christopher Morris, a free-lance photographer for the U.S. magazine
Newsweek, and Liliana Nieto, a photographer for the Long Island
daily Newsday. Those two and at least three others were treated at
Santa Maria Clinica for head injuries.
   On Thursday evening, photographers Sergio Lainz and Daniel Bush
from the Spanish news agency EFE were beaten by riot police in
front of the Defense Ministry, toward which they ran to get away
from tear gas.
   The government issued large, pink press credentials to reporters
covering Wednesday's national referendum, in which President Gen.
Augusto Pinochet lost his bid to extend his term in office until
1997. His defeat sets the stage for balloting in December 1989 that
would be the first presidential election since Pinochet, 72, seized
power by coup in September 1973.
   However, opposition groups, buoyed by their victory, now are
demanding that elections be held sooner. Pinochet's blunt refusal
Thursday night has hardened public opposition to his rule.
   After the demonstrations about 50 foreign journalists walked to
a National Police station and filed a complaint.
   Other journalists injured Friday evening included Fred Thys, a
stringer for the U.S. television network CBS, and cameraman Ricardo
Correa and soundman Leopoldo Vidal. All three are based in Buenos
Aires, Argentina. Agence France Presse photographer Cristobal
Bouroncle Sedane also was injured.
</TEXT>
