<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 0830EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Chernobyl     10-08 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Chernobyl,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Razing Chernobyl Town Because of Contamination</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Local authorities are razing the town of
Chernobyl, site of the world's worst nuclear power accident,
because its buildings will never be fit for human habitation,
Pravda said today.
   ``The radiation situation in Chernobyl is such that full life of
people cannot resume for decades,'' V. Komarov, chief engineer of
the nuclear power agency running the nearby Chernobyl power plant,
was quoted as saying.
   The town, which formerly had 10,000 residents, was evacuated in
April 1986 when a fire at the nuclear plant spewed radiation
worldwide. Officials said 31 people were killed.
   Authorities originally planned to tear down only dilapidated
houses, Komarov wrote in an article in the power plant newspaper
quoted by Pravda, the Soviet Communist Party's newspaper.
   But ``by the time normal life can return, all the houses will be
equally dilapidated and living in them will be impossible,'' he
said. ``In other words, there will be scarcely anything to preserve
at all!''
   Officials started by setting fire to one house and then
bulldozed two streets of homes in the center of the town, Pravda
said. Some of the buildings were just 3 years old.
   Pravda objected to the decision and pointed out that a similar
town, also 11 miles from the power plant, has been decontaminated
and repopulated.
   The revitalized town of Gden is in the Byelorussian republic
north of the Chernobyl power plant. The town of Chernobyl is in the
Ukraine.
   The area within six miles of the power plant is a preserve where
the effects of radiation on animals and plants is being studied.
Some workers come into the area on temporary duty, but no one is
allowed to live there.
   Pravda also reported that 994 people, mostly middle-aged and
elderly, have moved back into the Ukrainian section of the 18-mile
danger zone outside the uninhabitated ring.
   Reports this spring said 100 people returned to Chernobyl
itself, but Pravda said they were given no consideration in the
decision to raze the town.
   Gamma background radiation levels in Chernobyl were 0.1
milliroentgen per hour in June, equal to the natural radioactivity
in mountainous areas but twice that of the Ukrainian capital, Kiev,
south of Chernobyl, the newspaper said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
