<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Liberia-Treason     10-08 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Liberia-Treason,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Presidential Candidate, Nine Others Found Guilty In Coup
Plot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MONROVIA, Liberia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury found a former presidential
candidate and nine other people guilty of plotting to overthrow the
government and kill President Samuel K. Doe.
   Circuit Judge George Tulay said he will announce the sentences
soon.
   The defendants included teacher Gabriel Kpolleh, who ran in the
1985 presidential election as a candidate of the now banned Liberia
Unification Party, and a former associate judge, Cpehas Mbandi.
   Defense lawyers objected to Friday evening's verdict saying they
had information of tampering with the 14-member jury during the
eight-week trial. Tulay said he will consider the objections when
he receives written complaints.
   Hundreds of relatives and sympathizers in the courtroom and
outside wept when the verdict was announced.
   The defendants were among 14 people indicted by a grand jury in
March on charges of plotting to assassinate Doe and replace his
government with a People's Reorganization Council. Four of those
indicted have not been arrested.
   Prosecution witnesses said the defendants met several times
between 1986 and March this year to discuss their plans and had a
cache of grenades, rifles and ammunition to use in the takeover.
   Several attempts have been made to oust Doe, a former army
master sergeant, since he overthrew the government of William
Tolbert in 1980 and killed the civilian leader.
   More than 600 people were killed during a Nov. 12, 1985 coup
attempt, which followed elections that opposition leaders said were
rigged.
   In July, Doe said a 12-man invading force led by his former
second in command, Maj.-Gen. Nicholas Podier Jr., was intercepted
at the border with Ivory Coast, Liberia's eastern neighbor.
   Podier and four companions died in a firefight with Liberian
security men. Two Americans _ Curtis Williams, 45, of Jersey City,
N.J., and James Bush, 40, of Baltimore _ have been charged with
treason for their alleged role in the Podier plot to overthrow the
government.
   The West African nation was founded in 1847 by freed American
slaves.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
