<DOCNO> AP881008-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 0921EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Massacre     10-08 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Massacre,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviet Weekly Details Stalin-Era Massacre</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet weekly published an unusually detailed
account of a massacre in the Stalin era in which police lined more
than 100,000 people along ditches, gagged them and shot them,
sometimes using one bullet for two people.
   Although the 29-year reign of dictator Josef Stalin has recently
been fiercely criticized in the Soviet press, few articles have
gone as far as the Moscow News account of the massacre at Kuropaty,
near Minsk, in the 1930s.
   ``Gunshots resounded night and day, winter and summer, and there
were also cries ... prayers and moans,'' Moscow News wrote in an
article entitled ``Kuropaty, the Human Tragedy About Which Everyone
Must Know.''
   It said the police confronted a woodsman who saw freshly dug
mass graves and abandoned personal belongings near the killing site
and told him, ``See less, if you want to live.''
   The story in this week's issue combined personal accounts from
people who lived around the site with reports from recent
excavations to piece together what happened at Kuropaty.
   Men and women branded ``enemies of the people'' under Stalin
were brought alongside the newly dug ditches and made to stand in
rows, the paper said. They were then gagged and shot, it said.
   In some cases, the victims were made to stand so that one bullet
would kill two people, Moscow News said.
   For the NKVD secret police, who carried out the executions,
``this was their brand of bravado, of sport, a show of
professionalism,'' the paper said.
   Zenon Poznyak, an archaeologist who wrote the Moscow News story,
said the number of people buried at Kuropaty was estimated at
102,000 at the very least.
   ``However, the actual number of victims must be higher,''
Poznyak wrote.
   Moscow News and another weekly, Ogonyok, previously reported
that Soviet authorities after World War II tried to cover up what
happened at Kuropaty.
   As a result of the recent publicity, the Byelorussian
prosecutor's office has opened a criminal investigation into the
massacres, but state-run media have never said who might be
prosecuted or for what.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
