<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 0946EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Protest     10-08 0307</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Protest,0316</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leading British Writers Protest Indian Ban On Novel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six people, including playwright Tom Stoppard and
novelist Kingsley Amis, have signed a telegram to Indian Prime
Minister Rajiv Gandhi protesting the country's ban on Salman
Rushdie's new novel.
   The novel, ``The Satanic Verses,'' was banned by India's
Ministry of Finance after Moslem members of Parliament found the
book offensive to Islam.
   The complicated story, which mixes elements of realism and
fantasy, focuses on two Indian characters. The benevolent one acts
as a messenger for Mohammed, the founder of the Islamic religion.
The other is satanic and manipulative.
   Rushdie, 41, responded to the ban in a statement issued by Index
on Censorship, a British-based journal on issues of free speech
around the world.
   ``I feel very shocked by the news,'' the Bombay-born novelist
said. ``For India to describe itself, as it frequently does, as the
world's largest democracy is clearly incompatible with the act of
banning a work of literature.
   ``I very much hope that good sense can prevail and that this
decision can speedily be reversed so that Indian readers might have
a chance to judge the book for themselves,'' said Rushdie, whose
previous novels include ``Shame'' and ``Midnight's Children.''
   The protest telegram, which was sent Friday, said:
   ``We consider that the banning of a serious work of literature
represents a very grave threat to freedom of expression in your
country, and strongly urge you to ensure that the ban is lifted.''
   The other signers were poet Stephen Spender; Philip Spender and
Sally Laird, the director and editor, respectively, of Index on
Censorship; and Kevin Boyle, director of Article 19, a second
anti-censorship organization.
   ``The Satanic Verses'' was published Sept. 22 in Britain to
generally good reviews. It has been nominated for London's
prestigious Booker Prize, which will be announced Oct. 25.
</TEXT>
