<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HarveyTrial     10-08 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Harvey Trial,0405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Harvey Sentenced to Life for School Takeover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man has been sentenced to life in
prison after tearfully pleading guilty in a plea bargain agreement
to taking 110 children and adults hostage at a private school.
   James L. Harvey, 43, at his sisters' encouragement, pleaded
guilty Friday to one count of first-degree kidnapping and five
counts of second-degree kidnapping in the Feb. 2 takeover of West
End Christian School in Tuscaloosa.
   The plea cut short testimony in Harvey's trial, which had been
moved to Huntsville because of pretrial publicity.
   Circuit Judge John M. Karrh sentenced Harvey to one life term
and five 20-year terms, to be served concurrently. He said he would
recommend that Harvey get psychiatric help in prison.
   ``I think you need treatment,'' Karrh told the weeping Harvey,
who had maintained during the 12-hour siege and during his trial,
which began Wednesday, that he was exercising his constitutional
right to bear arms and was making a statement for the nation's
homeless, poor and illiterate.
   Before pleading guilty, Harvey, who had defended himself during
the trial, sat at the defense table and cried while he signed a
form that said he understood his rights.
   The original 110 kidnapping charges carried a maximum sentence
of up to 10,000 years. The charges were combined into six amended
counts after he agreed during negotiations Thursday night and
Friday to stop fighting the charges.
   Two older sisters, Doris Elliott and Martha Gray of Tuscaloosa,
took part in the talks.
   ``He is mentally and physically exhausted,'' Mrs. Gray said.
``I've thought all along that he needed mental help. I love him and
I want him well. ...
   ``All I wanted from the beginning was for him to get some help,
but he didn't agree until this morning that he needed help.''
   The trial's end saves Gov. Guy Hunt from having to testify.
Harvey had summoned him as a defense witness because the governor's
videotape of a bogus pardon had persuaded Harvey to put aside his
three high-powered guns and walk out of the school building exactly
12 hours after he and another man had entered the school.
   The other man, John Rhodes Jr., emerged during the afternoon of
the siege and also was charged with kidnapping but later was freed
after authorities determined that Harvey had tricked him into
helping him.
</TEXT>
