<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 1011EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ContaminatedCandy     10-08 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contaminated Candy,0414</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strychnine Found In Candy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELANIE MADER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators are looking for the source
of poison found in a package of Sunkist Fun Fruits and Dinosaurs
candy that has resulted in the candies being pulled from store
shelves in northern New Jersey.
   A woman discovered the poison, strychnine, after her 4-year-old
son ate some of the candy, which was purchased at a grocery store,
Bergen County prosecutor Larry McClure said at a news conference
Friday.
   The boy showed the candy to his mother and she noticed the
powdery coating. State police tests completed Friday identified the
substance.
   The boy did not become ill or need hospitalization, McClure
said. He said he did not know if any other contaminated boxes were
distributed.
   ``Information we have from interviews with the housewife and her
family (show) ... it (the poison) was more than likely (added)
during the manufacturing process or before packaging,'' McClure
said.
   Henry Heide Co. in New Brunswick made the candy for the Lipton
Co., which packaged and distributed the boxes under the Sunkist
label, McClure said.
   McClure said the prosecutor's office contacted the Lipton Co.,
which has cooperated in the investigation. He said they had not yet
contacted Heide.
   There was no immediate comment from the Heide company. A
production superviser, who refused to give his name, said he had
not heard about the contaminated candy. He said he would pass
messages to company officials. Other calls for comment were not
answered.
   Curt Anderson, a vice president for public affairs with Sunkist
in Sherman Oaks, Calif., told The Star-Ledger of Newark that the
case appears to be isolated, but that the boxes were pulled off
shelves as a precaution.
   McClure said the number on the outside of the box is 8H04EF. The
batch was packaged Aug. 4 and distributed in an area ranging from
Massachusetts to Florida and west to Ohio, McClure said.
   Lipton provided the distribution areas to the prosecutor, who
said he could not be more specific on states or stores.
   All the candy was being taken off the shelves in northern New
Jersey and authorities in potentially affected areas were notified,
McClure said.
   McClure would not identify the mother or child.
   Strychnine, commonly used in rodent killer, may cause death in
small doses or can cause violent convulsions, loss of muscle
control, intense pain and impaired respiration, McClure said.
</TEXT>
