<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GunStoreFire     10-08 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gun Store Fire,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire Destroys Gun Store, Kills Four People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Flying bullets forced firefighters to take
cover when an ammunition manufacturing company caught fire and
exploded, killing four people, authorities said.
   Investigators from the state Fire Marshal's Office and the
federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms worked today to
determine what caused the fire and explosions Friday at the Buffalo
Rock Shooters Supply, seven miles west of this north-central
Illinois town.
   The company makes ammunition and sells weapons to police
departments around the country, authorities said.
   ``I've seen explosions before, but nothing like this. It was
just so massive,'' La Salle County Coroner Marion Osborne said.
   ``It was a big ball of fire with a couple of explosions. There
were a lot of bullets flying,'' said Vince Dettore, fire chief of
Naplate, a town about four miles east of the factory.
   Dettore said workers at the company were believed to have been
making bullets when the first explosion hit about 11:30 a.m. in the
main building, which also housed the company's general offices and
gun shop.
   The official cause was unknown, but fire investigators suspect a
spark may have ignited gunpowder.
   ``It started in the main building where they make ammunition and
sell guns,'' Dettore said. ``A place like that with all that black
powder _ just the dust, if you get a spark in there that's all it's
going to take. They had cases and cases and cases of all kinds of
ammunition, all kinds of guns.''
   Bullets were whizzing through the air when firefighters arrived
at the complex, which also included three ammunition and gun
storage buildings, Dettore said.
   ``It's not as dangerous as if it was shot out of a gun itself,''
the fire chief said. ``It gets a little scarey when you get a big
explosion.
   ``We started putting it out until we were told there was black
powder in there and then I evacuated all of the men out,'' Dettore
said.
   He said the 40 firefighters retreated about a half-mile from the
complex for 45 minutes and then resumed battling the blaze.
   The victims, company owner Roger Fulmer, 53, of Ottawa; his
stepdaughter, Patti Smith, 32, of Utica; Pamela Ellsworth, 26, of
Wedron; and Ronea Scamen, 31, of Ottawa, were identified through
dental records, said Osborne.
</TEXT>
