<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Yugoslavia 4thLd-Writethru a0505 10-08 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0505,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Offers To Resign After Police Clash With Protesters</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Montenegro government
offering resignation. Pickup 4th graf pvs, ``More than...'' Edits
to conform.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government of Montenegro offered
its resignation to the republic's Parliament today after
club-wielding riot police clashed with thousands of protesters,
official media reported.
   The demonstrators in Titograd, the republic's capital, were
demanding the immediate removal of the local Communist leadership,
the state-run Tanjug news agency said. Montenegrin party leaders
held an emergency session to discuss the demand and tensions in the
region.
   Police dispersed the protesters in the latest clash in a growing
wave of economic and ethnic unrest in Yugoslavia's six republics
and two autonoous provinces. This was believed to be the first time
police used force.
   Tanjug said 23 demonstrators were detained for making
unspecified ``public hostile declarations,'' but most were later
released.
   About 10 protesters were injured, said a source in Titograd who
spoke on condition of anonymity. Tanjug said several demonstrators
were injured but did not provide figures.
   In Belgrade, the national capital, the ruling Communist Party
Presidium met today to discuss the developments in Montenegro.
   More than 20,000 people crowded into a square in the city late
Friday and stayed there all night, defying repeated police attempts
to disperse and demanding the ouster of the Communist Party
leadership, witnesses said.
   ``You betrayed us,'' chanted the crowd in Titograd, 280 miles
southwest of Belgrade. ``We want bread. Our children are hungry.''
   The flag-waving, emotional crowd tried several times to force
its way into the Parliament building but were prevented by police
and riot squads.
   At about 7 a.m., riot police charged with clubs, pushing the
crowd into a nearby park, Tanjug said.
   A police spokesman who demanded anonymity said police intervened
because of ``nationalistic, vulgar and hostile speeches'' delivered
by several people during the overnight meeting. He said police and
the town's authorities ``will not allow the continuation of the
rally because it has been abused by individuals to deliver hostile
slogans.''
   The mayor of Titograd, which has 150,000 inhabitants, has
announced his resignation, Tanjug said.
   The rally began after 1,000 construction workers went on strike
Friday to protest low wages and falling living standards.
   The Titograd protest was one of several demonstrations in
Yugoslavia that began Friday. On Thursday, 30,000 people surrounded
a government building in the province of Vojvodina, battling police
and eventually forcing the resignations of the 15-member provincial
Politburo.
   National Communist Party leaders tried to quell the growing
strife by promising changes in leadership.
   The ruling national Presidium issued a statement Friday saying
the policy-making Central Committee plenum to meet Oct. 17 ``will
make necessary personnel changes'' to deal with the crisis.
   A growing number of Yugoslavians have called for a top-level
shake-up as the unrest continues. The public protests stem from the
country's worst economic crisis in its history and long-simmering
feuds between ethnic groups.
   Communist leaders have been blamed for failing to defuse
tensions between the mostly Christian Slav minority and the largely
Moslem ethnic Albanian majority in the southern Kosovo province in
the republic of Serbia.
   The Presidium statement appealed for urgent changes in the
country's political and economic system to help resolved the crisis
over growing labor unrest, a 217 percent annual inflation and a $21
billion foreign debt.
</TEXT>
