<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--AlitaliaStrike     10-08 0139</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Alitalia Strike,0142</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italy's National Airline Strikes For Six Hours</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alitalia, Italy's national air carrier, canceled
dozens of domestic and international flights Saturday during a
six-hour strike by pilots, flight attendants, technicians and
ground personnel.
   A specially outfitted DC-9 of the Alitalia fleet, with Pope John
Paul II aboard, took off from Rome's Leonardo da Vinci Airport just
as the strike began. He was beginning a four-day visit to France.
   Airport officials said only domestic flights linking the
mainland to Sicily and Sardinia took off and landed regularly
during the work stoppage. Flights to Canada and the United States
were postponed until the strike ended at 2 p.m. Foreign carriers
were not involved.
   The strikers were protesting proposed budget cuts for the
airport administration and other services that they contend will
give them more work.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
