<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PedestriansKilled 2ndLd-Writethru a0515 10-08 0413</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pedestrians Killed, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0515,0419</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Five Girls Killed When Car Jumps Sidewalk</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to update with police comments re speed,
driver related to one victim, and CORRECT victim name Hylock to
Hylok, picking up at the 5th graf previous, ``The community.''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PULASKI, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five elementary school girls walking home
from a party were killed when a speeding car careened off a utility
pole and onto a sidewalk, authorities said.
   Police Chief Reed Woodward said today no alcohol was involved in
the accident. He said the driver was a diabetic but authorities
were uncertain whether that played a role in the crash. Police were
investigating reports that he may have had a seizure.
   He said the car may have been out of control for 1,500 feet.
   ``We do know that the vehicle was traveling at a high rate of
speed,'' Woodward said. ``This must have happened just incredibly
fast for these kids not to get out of the way.''
   He identified the five pedestrians killed as Nicole Watia, 12,
and Laura Karcz, Jessica McKeefry, Brenda Hylok and Jodi Prokop,
all 13. The girls were all from Pulaski or its outskirts.
   The car hit a tree after it struck the girls, police said. The
driver, Scott C. Karcz, 17, and his sister, a passenger, were taken
to Green Bay hospitals and underwent surgery this morning. Both
were in critical condition today, authorities said. He is a distant
relative of victim Laura Karcz, Woodward said.
   The community is a rural village of 1,875 about 15 miles
northwest of Green Bay.
   Because of the tragedy, the high school canceled today's
football game, Principal Guy David said.
   ``The entire community is in a state of shock,'' David said.
``This is going to be a real problem for the community to deal
with. In a small community like this, everybody knows everybody.''
   Phil Rusniak, 70, who lives near the crash site, said he was
eating supper when he heard the accident outside his home.
   ``Everything was laying out in the street. It's terrible,''
Rusniak said.
   Jerome Karcz, the father of the driver, told WFRV-TV in Green
Bay that his son and daughter were returning to the high school to
get their textbooks when the accident occurred.
   A bomb threat had been made at the school Friday and officials
dismissed students early, authorities said. No explosives were
found and children were permitted back into the school to pick up
belongings.
</TEXT>
