<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 1200EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Korea-Politics     10-08 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea-Politics,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Governing Party Blasts Opposition Officials For Joining Radical
Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The governing party sharply criticized
opposition parties Saturday after secretaries of some opposition
lawmakers helped radical students seize the office of a federal
legislator.
   Prosecutor-general Lee Jong-nam ordered a probe of the clash, in
which some opposition officials attacked police with broken
ashtrays, flowerpots and fire extinguishers and shouted slogans.
   ``It is a clear case of blocking the execution of official
duties by police. All opposition secretaries and officials found
involved will be arrested and punished,'' Lee said.
   Twenty-three radical students were arrested for seizing the
office of Chung Ho-yang, a former defense minister and now a
ranking member of the governing Democratic Justice Party. The
incident occurred Thursday.
   The students were demanding the arrest of former President Chun
Doo-hwan and his wife for alleged corruption. Chun left office in
Feburary.
   The governing party ran huge advertisements in almost all daily
newspapers on Saturday, condemning the attack as an open challenge
to democratic development. The ads said the attackers were
``leftist radicals'' trying to overthrow the government.
   The three main opposition parties said the government was
overreacting in an effort to take attention away from allegations
of corruption during Chun's rule. A parliamentary investigation is
focusing on the allegations.
   Roh succeeded Chun after winning presidential elections in
December. Opposition officials charge that Roh is reluctant to
divulge wrongdoing by his predecessor.
   The dispute appeared to end a short truce between the government
and opposition parties during the Olympics, which ended Oct. 2.
</TEXT>
