<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 1203EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 1stLd-Writethru a0434 10-08 0905</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0434,910</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Keeps Up Law-and-Order Theme; Dukakis Campaigns In Maine</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 15 grafs with Bush, Bentsen remarks, picking
up in 12th graf pvs, Fuller said</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush, concluding a week of attacks on Democrat
Michael Dukakis' stands on crime, accepted the endorsement of the
head of a national police group today, then said in answer to
reporters' questions that he has not been trying to distance
himself from running mate Dan Quayle.
   Bush said he was getting ``a little tired of erroneous reporting
out there'' that has noted his relative lack of comment on Quayle
since Wednesday night's vice presidential debate, which polls show
most people thought Quayle lost to Democrat Lloyd Bentsen.
   ``This concept that I see in some of these reports that I am not
supportive of Dan Quayle are absolutely ludicrous,'' he said.
``They are ridiculous. He did well in that debate. He has my full
support ... and I made a good decision'' in selecting the Indiana
senator as running mate.
   Bush commented in Washington after accepting the endorsement of
Dewey Stokes, president of the National Fraternal Order of Police.
A news release from the Bush campaign emphasized the 197,000-person
membership of the organization, but Stokes acknowledged he was only
giving his personal support, not that of the group, which has not
taken a position on the race.
   Dukakis, meanwhile, was heading for Maine today, after a speech
Friday in which he stood in a Missouri auto parts plant owned by
Italians and attacked foreign ownership of American firms.
   Lloyd Bentsen, the Democratic vice presidential nominee, said
today in Texas he wouldn't let the Republicans concentrate only on
Bush and keep the spotlight off Dan Quayle, the GOP running mate
whom Bentsen debated Wednesday night.
   He said the GOP had made a mistake in choosing ``a candidate
that the imagemakers and the poll takers thought could be packaged
and sold to the American people.''
   As for Dukakis' speech Friday, campaign aides, moving quickly to
say that he was not criticizing any company in particular,
acknowledged that he didn't know the Moog Automotive Inc. plant in
suburban St. Louis had foreign owners.
   ``If anyone asks you what's at stake in this election, just
remind them of that moment in the debate Wednesday night when
Senator Quayle said he's happy that foriegn owners are buying up
America,'' Dukakis said.
   ``Maybe the Republican ticket wants our children to work for
foreign owners, pay rent to foreign owners, and owe their future to
foreign owners _ but that's not the kind of future Lloyd Bentsen
and I and (Missouri Rep.) Dick Gephardt want for America,'' he
continued.
   The Moog family sold the company more than 10 years ago to IFINT
USA, the American subsidiary of IFI of Turin, Italy. IFI is owned
by the Agnelli family, which also owns the automaker Fiat.
   Dukakis later said of the incident, ``It was not a faux pas.''
   The candidates made their rounds as sponsors of next week's
second and final presidential debate said the event would be held
Thursday or Friday night on the UCLA campus in Los Angeles
beginning at 9 p.m. EDT. The 90-minute encounter will be televised
nationally.
   Bush, who has made Massachusetts' former prison furlough program
the centerpiece of his soft-on-crime attack against Dukakis, has
been criticized by the Dukakis camp for making such charges when he
is vice president of the federal government which also has a
furlough program.
   ``There's no question that the federal furlough program should
be reviewed,'' Bush's chief of staff, Craig Fuller told reporters
on Friday. ``We talked about it today. ... George Bush would have
his attorney general do that.''
   Fuller said the Repbulican candidate had no specific proposal to
revise the current law and that Bush was satisfied it is
``fundamentally different'' from the Massachusetts law that granted
a weekend furlough in 1986 to convicted murderer Willie Horton.
   In a campaign speech Friday in Xenia, Ohio, Bush charged that
Dukakis as Massachusetts governor ``relented'' and repealed the law
that let murderers go on weekend furlough ``under the bright
spotlight of the national presidential campaign.''
   In some of the harshest language he has used to describe Dukakis
as soft on crime, Bush accused his rival of having compassion for
criminals but ``an astounding lack of sensitivity'' for crime
victims.
   With one month to go to the election, the polls continued to
show Bush a step ahead in the race for the White House. Democrats
were hoping that other polls rating Bentsen as the winner of the
vice presidential debate would serve as prelude to a shift in the
presidential race itself.
   GOP vice presidential candidate Quayle laughed at that, as he
shrugged off Democratic campaign commercials aimed at raising
doubts about his fitness for high office.
   ``We can stand the heat. We're going to stay in the kitchen.
George Bush is going to be the next president of the United States.
The voters will vote for him,'' the Indiana senator said as he
campaigned in Tennessee.
   Bentsen chipped in on the Democratic anti-Quayle barrage, saying
it was an ``incredible misfit'' for his vice presidential rival to
compare his own experience in Congress with John Kennedy's before
the 1960 election. Quayle's self-comparison produced the most
riveting moment of the debate, when Bentsen turned to him and said,
``Senator, you're no Jack Kennedy.''
</TEXT>
