<1ST_LINE>u a PM-SpaceShuttle     10-08 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Space Shuttle,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Discovery Departs California On Piggyback Jet Ride To Florida</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Arrival in San Antonio expected at 2:30 p.m EDT and arrival
in Florida set for about 8:30 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The space shuttle
Discovery left its landing site today atop a jumbo jet for the trip
home to Florida five days after completing America's first space
flight since the Challenger tragedy.
   The modified Boeing 747, carrying the shuttle piggyback, took
off from this Mojave Desert military base at 7:54 a.m., said Nancy
Lovato, spokeswoman for the National Aeronautics and Space
Administration.
   ``It was a fitting finish to a super mission,'' Ms. Lovato said.
``It was the prettiest takeoff from here that I've ever seen, and
I've seen them all.''
   The jet was expected to arrive at Kennedy Space Center in
Florida late today after a refueling stop at Kelly Air Force Base
in San Antonio, Texas.
   Discovery and its five-man crew landed on the hard clay Rogers
Dry Lake bed last Monday, four days after launch from Cape
Canaveral, Fla., on the first shuttle flight since Challenger
exploded on Jan. 28, 1986, killing all seven crew members.
   Since Discovery landed in California, NASA workers have toiled
to prepare it for its ride to Florida. They photographed and
replaced damaged heat-shield tiles, purged fuel from its main
engines and orbital maneuvering engines, installed a tailcone and
locks to prevent control surfaces from fluttering on the ride home,
then hoisted it to its perch atop the jet.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
