<DOCNO> AP881008-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 1216EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0443 10-08 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0443,760</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Endorsed by Police Official, Supports Quayle</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Bush remarks in top 12 grafs, picking up in 6th
graf pvs, In a</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican George Bush today denounced as
``absolutely ludicrous'' any notion that he is trying to keep his
distance from running mate Dan Quayle.
   ``He's doing just fine,'' Bush said in answer to a question from
reporters after he accepted the endorsement of a law enforcement
official. ``I support him very strongly.''
   Bush added with apparent anger in his voice, ``This concept that
I see in some of these reports that I am not supportive of Dan
Quayle are absolutely ludicrous.''
   ``They are ridiculous,'' he said. ``He did well in that debate.
He has my full support ... and I made a good decision'' in
selecting the Indiana senator.
   Bush said he gets ``a little tired of erroneous reporting out
there.''
   He was endorsed today by Dewey Stokes, president of the National
Fraternal Order of Police, who called Bush ``the law enforcement
candidate.''
   However, while a news release from the Bush campaign touted the
197,000-person membership of Stokes' organization, Stokes
acknowledged that he was only giving his personal support, not that
of the organization, which has not taken a position.
   Bush has made Massachusetts' former prison furlough program the
centerpiece of his soft-on-crime attack against presidential rival
Michael Dukakis, but a top aide said Friday that Bush believes the
federal prison furlough program should be reviewed as well.
   Dukakis aides have criticized Bush for attacking Dukakis on the
subject while Bush is vice president of a federal system that also
has a furlough program.
   ``There's no question that the federal furlough program should
be reviewed,'' Bush's chief of staff, Craig Fuller, told reporters
on Friday. ``We talked about it today ... George Bush would have
his attorney general do that.''
   Fuller said the Republican candidate had no specific proposal to
revise the current law, and that Bush was satisfied it is
``fundamentally different'' from the Massachusetts law that granted
a weekend furlough in 1986 to convicted murderer Willie Horton.
   Questions about the federal furlough program arose as Bush
stepped up his attack against Dukakis over the furlough program in
the Democratic governor's home state.
   In a campaign speech Friday in Xenia, Ohio, Bush charged that
Dukakis as governor ``relented'' and repealed the law that let
murderers go on weekend furlough ``under the bright spotlight of
the national presidential campaign'' this year.
   Bush called Dukakis ``the furlough king'' later at an outdoor
rally of several thousand pople in Medina, an affluent white suburb
of Cleveland.
   He continued the tough-on-crime talk at a later rally at Lee's
Summit High School in Missouri before returning to Washington.
   He said Dukakis has always espoused liberal views.
   ``What I fault him for is trying to now be something he is
not,'' Bush told the packed high school gym.
   Reporters were denied access to Bush, as has been the case since
last week, but the campaign put out an information sheet when asked
what Bush had to say on the federal government's own furlough
program.
   It said the federal furloughs are granted only within two years
of a prisoner's release date.
   The Massachusetts program was more lenient, Fuller said, citing
the Horton case in which Horton bludgeoned a Maryland couple,
raping the woman, after escaping during a weekend furlough.
   Fuller said Horton could not have been furloughed under the
federal program, which is available only to prisoners in
``community custody,'' the lowest security level in the federal
prison system.
   In some of the harshest language he has used to describe Dukakis
as soft on crime, Bush alleged Friday that his rival has compassion
for criminals but ``an astounding lack of sensitivity'' for crime
victims.
   ``He still clings to a discredited liberal ideology that blinds
him to the true causes of crime, and the often devastating effects
it has on innocent people,'' Bush said in the Xenia speech to law
enforcement officials and supporters.
   ``I'm not faulting the governor of Maassachusetts for one error
in judgment. But it concerns me deeply that in all this time, as
far as I know, the governor has never acknowledged that his
furlough program was a mistake,'' Bush said.
   ``On no other issue is my opponent's philosophy so completely at
odds with mine, and I would say, with the common sense attitudes of
the American people, than on the issue of crime,'' Bush said.
   Another crime-oriented speech is set for Monday in New Jersey,
campaign aides said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
