<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon     10-08 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hoss Rejects U.N. Role in Presidential Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leader of Lebanon's Syrian-backed
Cabinet on Saturday opposed deploying U.N. peacekeeping troops to
supervise deadlocked presidential elections. The proposal is backed
by a rival Christian Cabinet.
   ``There are practical procedural difficulties at the United
Nations in assigning U.N. forces internal missions like supervision
of security for the presidential election session,'' Acting Prime
Minister Salim Hoss told reporters before leaving for talks in
Damascus, the Syrian capital.
   He planned to discuss the presidential election with officials
there.
   ``The reasons behind the failure to elect a president have not
been related to security issues so far, but to the lack of
consensus on the president's identity and his political line,''
Hoss said.
   Lebanon's government splintered into rival Moslem and Christian
factions after Parliament failed to elect a new president when Amin
Gemayel's term expired Sept. 22.
   A French proposal to deploy U.N. forces in Beirut to oversee the
election was endorsed by Lebanon's Christian militia commander,
Samir Geagea, on Thursday.
   Geagea, who opposes Syria's involvement in Lebanon, backs the
Christian Cabinet headed by the army commander, Gen. Michel Aoun.
   Syria, the main power broker in Lebanon, maintains 40,000 troops
in eastern and northern provinces as well as in the Moslem western
and southern sectors of Beirut.
   Parliament failed to elect a new president due to a lack of
quorum following a boycott by Christian deputies.
   Gemayel, acting minutes before the expiration of his term,
appointed Gen. Aoun, a Maronite Catholic, to head a six-man interim
Cabinet.
   Syrian-backed Moslem and leftist leaders have rejected Aoun's
cabinet, continuing to recognize Hoss' five-man body that ruled
during Gemayel's term.
</TEXT>
