<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Vietnam-USMIAs     10-08 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vietnam-US MIAs,0211</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Experts Fly To Vietnam For Talks On Missing Servicemen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A U.S. military team flew to Vietnam on
Saturday to discuss further efforts to resolve the fates of
American servicemen missing in the Vietnam War.
   The experts planned to review results of the first
U.S.-Vietnamese joint field investigation, which was completed
Tuesday after the retrieval of plane wreckage and two sets of human
remains.
   Talks were scheduled in the capital, Hanoi, with officials from
Vietnam's Office For Seeking Missing Personnel.
   The team included Lt. Col. Joe Harvey, commander of the U.S.
Joint Casualty Resolution Center and Lt. Col. Johnie Webb,
commander of the Army Central Identification Laboratory. Both units
based in Honolulu are seeking to resolve the fates of America's
wartime missing.
   Foreign Minister Nguyen Co Thach of Vietnam said last week his
government has agreed in principle to many projects over the next
two months to resolve the 70 MIA cases that Washington considers
top priority.
   A total of 2,393 Americans are listed as missing in action in
the Vietnam War, 1,757 of them in Vietnamese territory and the
others in Laos and Cambodia. The war ended when communist North
Vietnam defeated U.S.-backed South Vietnam in April 1975.
</TEXT>
