<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 1250EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-GovernorsAsPresident 1stLd-Writethru a0530 10-08 0906</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Governors As President, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0530,910</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Trying to Overcome Lack of Defense, Foreign Policy
Experience</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS 9th graf, Only two, to delete Coolidge, who had been
vice president. Story also moved in advance.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential nominee Michael
Dukakis is trying hard to beat the rap that his experience as a
governor has not equipped him to handle national defense and
foreign policy.
   He has talked tough on military spending and driven an M-1 tank;
met with foreign leaders from Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard
Shevardnadze to French President Francois Mitterrand, and he has
extolled the virtues of governors who became president.
   Or three of them, anyway.
   ``Some of our finest presidents, some of our strongest
international leaders, were governors: Franklin Roosevelt, Woodrow
Wilson, Theodore Roosevelt,'' Dukakis said in the first
presidential debate.
   He did not mention the last two presidents, both of them former
governers whose foreign policy performances have brought mixed
reviews.
   Ronald Reagan, a two-term California governor, is regularly
lambasted by critics who say he is unfamiliar with the nitty gritty
of national security. He is faulted for such acts as the 1983
invasion of Grenada and the 1986 bombing of Libya and for moving
slowly on arms control. His record as president will be tainted by
the Iran-Contra affair, as well.
   Jimmy Carter, who was governor of Georgia, is blamed by
conservatives for reacting poorly to revolutions in Iran and
Nicaragua and for allowing U.S. influence abroad to deteriorate.
   If elected, Dukakis would be the third man in a row to move from
the state house to the White House without having held a senior
federal job.
   Only one other former governor, Wilson of New Jersey, has become
president in this century without previously holding top elected or
appointed federal office.
   Franklin Roosevelt, lauded by Dukakis, was assistant secretary
of the Navy during World War I before he served as governor of New
York. Theodore Roosevelt held identical posts at the turn of the
century before becoming vice president and then president.
   Dukakis doesn't have those entries on his resume, but like
others before him, he is trying to ``create a lot of ersatz
credentials'' in foreign policy, said Stephen Hess, who was an aide
to former President Nixon.
   ``They go on trade missions. They join the Council on Foreign
Relations or the Trilateral Commission, which is what Carter did,''
said Hess, now a scholar at the liberal Brookings Institution in
Washington.
   Or they ride tanks and meet with foreign leaders.
   Governors who are elected president ``rely on a brain trust. But
so does everybody else, too, as the field becomes more
specialized,'' said Hess. ``Even Richard Nixon, who was truly
engaged in foreign policy and made it his life interest, brought in
specialists,'' notably Henry Kissinger, who served as his national
security adviser.
   Graham T. Allison Jr., a Dukakis foreign policy adviser, says
the Massachusetts governor's ``style as a leader and governor is
quite different from either Reagan or Carter.''
   Dukakis' ideas ``come out of interaction with other folks. There
is a combination of progressive values and pragmatism that is
something special. It is not classic liberalism,'' said Allison.
   Carter's view of the world was shaped by his career as a
submarine officer in the Navy and his devotion to his Baptist faith.
   He appointed a strong-minded national security adviser, Zbigniew
Brzezinski, a Columbia University professor of Soviet affairs, born
in Poland and deeply suspicious of the Kremlin.
   Carter appointed a very different personality as his secretary
of state, Cyrus Vance, a Wall Street lawyer and veteran of senior
government appointments who was deeply committed to diplomacy and
negotiations.
   ``There were two world-views spinning around'' at the top level
of government, said Hess, and the result was a sometimes confused
and vacillating approach to foreign affairs that ultimately brought
Vance's resignation.
   Allison said ``Carter was very interested in detail. He had
difficulty keeping his mind focused on the big picture, and was
unable to resist an overly expansive agenda.''
   ``Reagan is very effective at projecting a few central themes
but does not involve himself directly in the issues, neither in the
broad shape of the issues or in the details. But he has kept in
mind a few simple things and knows what a manageable agenda is,''
said Allison, who is dean of the John F. Kennedy School of
Government at Harvard University, where Dukakis once taught and
where he turns for much of his foreign policy advice.
   Conflicting views of the world at the top of the administration
``were not Reagan's problem,'' Hess said. ``He had a distinct point
of view that the people who were working for him had no trouble
following.''
   Reagan survived several overseas debacles, including the bombing
of the Marine Corps barracks in Beirut in 1983, but his hands-off
management style contributed to the worst policy crisis of his
administration, the exchange of arms for hostages with Iran.
   Clearly ``Reagan has had trouble with national security
advisers,'' running through six in seven years, said Hess.
   Dukakis has not said publicly who he might appoint national
security adviser or secretary of state if he is elected. But among
those often mentioned for those two important posts are Allison and
two colleagues from the Kennedy School, Joseph Nye and Albert
Carnesdale, along with Madeleine Albright, a Czechoslovakian-born
Georgetown University professor who served in the Carter White
House.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
