<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Reagan-DrugBill     10-08 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Drug Bill,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Pushes Senate to Act on Tough Sanctions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan, contending the American
people have ``had it'' with drug users and pushers, today exhorted
the Senate to approve tough, House-passed anti-drug legislation
before adjourning next week.
   ``Time is fast running out,'' Reagan said in his weekly radio
address, delivered from his weekend retreat at Camp David, Md.
   ``I want all Americans to take heart. This war is not yet won,
not by a long shot, but we are doing better and our nation is
united against this scourge as never before,'' Reagan said.
   The House has passed one version of the legislation, but the
measure has not yet come before the full Senate.
   ``The House bill has many good and tough provisions that express
our national commitment to five simple but powerful words _ those
words are `zero tolerance' and `Just say no,''' Reagan said,
lifting the slogan from his wife Nancy's anti-drug education
campaign.
   ``By zero tolerance, we mean simply, that we've had it,'' Reagan
said. ``We will no longer tolerate those who sell drugs and those
who buy drugs.
   ``All Americans of good will are determined to stamp out those
parasites who survive and even prosper by feeding off the energy
and vitality and humanity of others. They must pay,'' he said.
   Reagan pointed out that the bill passed by the House earlier
this month on a 375-30 vote includes the death penalty for those
who kill a law enforcement officer or authorizes the killing of
anyone in a drug-related crime.
   ``We must, we need and we will have this law,'' he said.
   Reagan also put in a plug for Vice President George Bush,
calling the GOP presidential candidate his ``point man'' on the
administration's anti-drug fight.
   Senators have been negotiating privately over crucial
time-limiting agreements that would enable Congress to pass the
anti-drug measure before adjournment, expected to come at the end
of next week.
   A bipartisan group of sponsors introduced the drug measure in
the Senate on Monday. But they agreed the Senate will run out of
time if long debates ensue over controversial issues such as user
penalties and allowing the admission in federal court of evidence
seized illegally, but in ``good faith.''
</TEXT>
