<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 1305EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CampaignProfessionals Bjt   10-08 1111</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campaign Professionals, Bjt,1090</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GOP Pros a Plus for Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The setting sun was glaring into camera
lenses, it was late in the afternoon, and Michael Dukakis was doing
the main ``visual'' of his campaign day, helping to destroy
confiscated drugs at an incinerator in suburban Detroit. But few
Americans would ever see it.
   The event was too late to make it onto the evening TV news, the
low angle of the sun made photographs difficult if not impossible,
and even those at the site _ squinting to see _ could not make out
exactly what it was that the Democratic presidential nominee was
doing.
   That same day, rival George Bush was on the scene for the
majestic landing of the space shuttle Discovery.
   The two events, and the way that campaign strategists set up
their respective candidate's participation in them, helps dramatize
the differences between the two campaigns _ although, to be sure,
Bush is able to capitalize on events he can attend like the
Discovery landing by virtue of his current office.
   While the vice president's campaign is by most accounts slick
and polished, the Dukakis campaign remains, according to critics,
uneven and sometimes amateurish.
   Some observers suggest that the number of seasoned veterans in
Bush's campaign, beginning at the top with former Treasury
Secretary James A. Baker III, a veteran of three past presidential
campaigns, is a prime reason for the skill and quick reaction time
often shown by the GOP campaign.
   Baker's guiding hand on the campaign of his longtime friend is
also widely viewed as a main reason why Bush has emerged since the
GOP convention in August as more aggressive and less frantic than
he appeared before.
   However, observers also suggest that Dukakis' high command is
improving on logistics and strategy, particularly with the
re-appearance of veteran John Sasso on Labor Day as the campaign's
chief strategist.
   Susan Estrich, who worked in the presidential campaigns of
Walter Mondale in 1984 and Edward Kennedy in 1980, remains Dukakis'
campaign manager.
   ``Mike Dukakis is an outsider whose team was largely composed of
veterans of Massachusetts politics. And he's been slower to
integrate the professionals,'' said Norman Ornstein, a political
analyst with the conservative American Enterprise Institute.
   Ornstein said that Bush is ``an insider, who pulled in inside
people around him.''
   The Bush campaign over the past few weeks:
   _ Twice raided Dukakis' home state to pick up the endorsements
of police organizations, part of Bush's effort to portray his rival
as soft on crime.
   _ Moved quickly, after the first nationally televised
presidential debate, to say that Bush did not want to make women
who seek abortions guilty of criminal activity, even after he had
left the issue vague.
   _ Has made the most of staged visual events to get on the
evening news, sticking to one message each day and reinforcing it
with photogenic campaign events.
   Bush doesn't just show up at campaign events. He makes
entrances. Bands play, thousands of balloons go up. At a rally in
Owensboro, Ky., last week, Bush arrived on a brightly decorated
riverboat. And traveling across Illinois by bus, he brought his own
warm-up group with him: country singers Crystal Gayle and Loretta
Lynn.
   Bush's campaign team is several layers deep.
   His main campaign staff includes such professionals as campaign
manager Lee Atwater, an official in President Reagan's 1980 and
1984 campaigns; pollster Robert S. Teeter, who has worked on every
presidential race for the past two decades, and Roger Ailes, who
was chief media consultant for Richard Nixon in 1972 and for a host
of GOP candidates since.
   The first team is augmented by GOP consultants who don't draw a
regular salary but whose expertise is routinely called on _ and who
have narrow, specific assignments.
   For instance, Charles Black, who has worked two past
presidential campaigns, is currently focusing just on Texas.
   Eddie Mahe Jr., a longtime GOP consultant, has one job with the
campaign: studying Dukakis' daily campaign techniques and reporting
back on which ones seem to be working.
   Richard Bond, Bush's national political director, was assigned
to keep an eye on New Jersey, then over the past few days was
reassigned to travel with GOP vice presidential candidate Dan
Quayle to oversee a program of damage control after the vice
presidential debate.
   He joins another political veteran, Stuart Spencer, who was
assigned full-time to Quayle at the GOP convention.
   Bush himself seldom gets involved with day-to-day strategy.
Dukakis does.
   Asked whether he had seen his recent campaign ads attacking
Quayle, Dukakis said: ``Are you kidding? Nothing goes on around
here without me knowing.''
   Meanwhile, Dukakis' circle of top-level advisers has been
changing _ in part in reaction to Democratic critics who said the
campaign had not brought in experienced party leaders.
   For instance, Dukakis on recent campaign trips has been
accompanied by Theodore C. Sorenson, a former speechwriter to John
Kennedy.
   Also, traveling with Dukakis in recent days have been Washington
lawyers and longtime Democratic political consultants Stephen
Engelberg and Peter Edelman. And Robert Schrum, veteran of Sen.
Edward Kennedy's presidential bid, has been brought in to bolster
the speechwriting staff.
   Campaign chairman Paul Brountas travels nearly everywhere with
Dukakis. He is a respected Boston corporate lawyer and a long-time
friend of Dukakis. His last national campaign experience was with
Edmund Muskie.
   Francis O'Brien, a veteran campaign aide and occasional movie
producer, has taken on a more visible role since the return of
Sasso. O'Brien now travels with Dukakis and is trying to coordinate
the political message with what appears on television.
   Kirk O'Donnell, a former aide to then-House Speaker Thomas P.
``Tip'' O'Neill, was brought in last spring and given a large role
in shaping the political message.
   The campaign has also brought in a few aides from other
Democratic campaigns. Larry Harrington, political director for the
Albert Gore campaign, is Dukakis' Southern coordinator. Richard
Moe, a Washington lawyer who was with Gephardt, is an occasional
adviser. Donna Brazille, from the Jesse Jackson campaign, sometimes
travels with Dukakis.
   Thomas Donilon, a top official with Walter Mondale's 1984
campaign, helped coordinate debate preparation.
   Still, few of these individuals have extensive experience in
presidential campaigns.
   ``I think the Democrats have been behind on that for some time,
even though they're beginning to catch up,'' said Bob Beckel,
former campaign manager for Mondale.
   ``Bush and his people used the period from the spring to the
convention very well to bring in the best talent in their party.
And they made a much faster transition from the primary to the
general election than did the Dukakis campaign,'' Beckel said.
</TEXT>
