<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Budget     10-08 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Budget,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Politburo Discusses Budget Cut, Making Ruble Convertible</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The ruling Politburo is considering cutting the
national budget and discussed making the ruble a convertible
currency, the Communist Party daily Pravda said Saturday.
   The newspaper said the subjects were discussed Thursday during a
session on the 1989 budget.
   Pravda said the 12-man Politburo discussed ``steps to make the
ruble a convertible currency.'' It did not explain further.
   Some Soviet economists have argued for making the ruble
convertible, so it could be transferred into other currencies on
the world market.
   This would remove a major stumbling block to trade, but it would
likely cause runaway inflation because the ruble's value would drop.
   The newspaper also did not give any details on the plans to cut
the budget, which is reportedly running at a deficit of more than
$100 billion. It said only that there were plans to ``reduce
expenses in all areas of the economy.''
   The newspaper Sovietskaya Rossiya reported last month that the
country is running a budget deficit of at least 73 billion rubles,
or $116 billion. The U.S. budget deficit is $150 billion.
   The Soviet deficit amounts to about 15 percent of the budget,
which is about $773 billion, Sovietskaya Rossiya said.
   It blamed the deficit on the cost of cleaning up the Chernobyl
nuclear power plant disaster, lower income to the state from
slashed vodka sales, and the falling price of oil. The Soviet Union
is the world's biggest oil exporter.
   Pravda said that while the Politburo wants to reduce expenses,
it also decided to improve the supply of food and consumer goods.
There were no details.
   Consumers surrounded Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev on
visit last month to Siberia and complained that his plans for
perestroika, or restructuring of the economy and society, have not
solved chronic shortages of food and housing.
   The Politburo reviews the budget, which is then rubber stamped
by the Supreme Soviet, or legislature. The Supreme Soviet is
scheduled to take up the budget in a session later this month.
</TEXT>
