<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SurfRescue     10-08 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Surf Rescue,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Coast Guardsmen Brave Pounding Surf, Stiff Winds In Rescue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NARRAGANSETT, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Coast Guardsmen braved six-foot
waves and near-gale-force wind to swim out to rescue six people
whose sailboat had been driven onto rocks during stormy weather,
the Coast Guard said Saturday.
   ``That boat was really taking a pounding in the surf,'' said
Petty Officer 3rd Class William J. Murray. ``We knew we had to take
the people off right then, and the only way to get to them was to
send rescue swimmers to them through the surf.''
   The 38-foot sloop Triple Creme, headed from New York to Newport,
was driven onto the rocks at Point Judith Light late Friday by a
stiff east wind.
   A Coast Guard petty officer who happened to look out the window
of the Point Judith station saw the boat on the rocks, amid waves
that were topping six feet, Murray said.
   Petty Officer 3rd Class John C. Hunter of Norton, Mass., and
Seaman Todd Dillinger of Fowlerville, Mich., donned rubber suits,
lifejackets and swimmers' harnesses, and breasted the waves and
35-mph wind, he said.
   One at a time, they ferried three of the people back to shore,
Murray said.
   Hunter and Dillinger then swam out to the boat again, rigged its
life raft and guided the raft and the other three occupants to
safety, he said.
   ``It looked pretty hairy, but everybody made it okay,'' Murray
said.
   ``Everybody was fine _ a little wet and scared,'' Murray said.
   He identified the rescued people as Steve Kaufman, 24, and
Michael Kim, 25, of New York City; Patricia Mi, 25, and Laura
Makatani, 23, of Washington; Joseph T. Seko, 28, of Middletown,
N.J.; and Vida Wu, 28, of Greenwich, Conn.
</TEXT>
