<DOCNO> AP881008-0089 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 1336EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Domes     10-08 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Domes,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Evidence Assembled in Washington on Rome's Cathedral</HEAD>
<HEAD>By CARL HARTMAN</HEAD>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The biggest show of Michelangelo drawings ever
exhibited in this country will give Americans a unique chance to
judge a major argument among art-lovers: did he design a round dome
for St. Peter's in Rome, or the taller dome St. Peter's now has,
like the U.S. Capitol?
   Originally the Capitol, built and rebuilt three centuries after
St. Peter's, had a round dome.
   The exhibit called ``Michelangelo: Draftsman@Architect'' opens
Sunday at the National Gallery of Art.
   One of the people who put it all together was Henry A. Millon,
dean of the museum's Center for Advanced Study in the Visual Arts.
He wrote in the catalogue that never, before this exhibition, has
so much of the evidence on St. Peter's dome been brought together.
   ``If you are an Anglo-American scholar or a German scholar, you
believe that Michelangelo in the period 1558-61 built the model
that he intended (for) St. Peter's..., a model with a hemispherical
inner and outer dome,'' he told a news conference.
   ``If you are (an) Italian or French (scholar) you believe that
after the model was finished in 1561 he changed his mind and
decided to elevate the outer dome, to the profile that it has
today.''
   The wooden model itself, 16.5 feet high and made under
Michelangelo's direction, is part of the exhibit. It has the same
elongated dome seen on the cathedral today.
   But some scholars believe the shape of both the model, and the
actual dome, was changed on the orders of Giacomo Della Porta, who
finished the dome after Michelangelo's death.
   Also on show is a pen-and-ink drawing attributed to a Frenchman,
Etienne Duperac, from the period between Michelangelo's death and
the completion of the dome. It says:
   ``This building, following the design of (Michelangelo)
Buonarotti, will be finished in this manner...''
   It depicts a round dome, not an elongated one.
   Another feature of the show is a newly-identified Michelangelo
drawing of the suicide of Cleopatra, never shown publicly before.
   Among the unusual pieces is a drawing in black chalk of the
torture of Tityus, a figure in Greek mythology who was punished by
having an enormous bird tear at his vitals. Michelangelo held the
drawing up to the light, traced it on the other side of the paper,
elimninated the bird, added a Roman soldier and presented the
result as a resurrected Christ.
   The show will be open in the gallery's West Building until Dec.
11. After that, the part of the show that consists mainly of figure
drawings will go to the Louvre in Paris.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881008-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 1356EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush     10-08 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Gets Police Leader's Endorsement, Defends Quayle</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, dogged by questions about his
embattled running mate, fought to keep the spotlight on his
tough-on-crime message Saturday by collecting another
law-enforcement endorsement.
   After the event, he said it was ``absolutely ludicrous'' to
suggest his support of Sen. Dan Quayle has lagged since Wednesday
night's vice presidential debate.
   Bush's latest in a series of endorsement announcements came from
Dewey Stokes, president of the national Fraternal Order of Police,
who called Bush ``the law enforcement candidate.''
   While a fact sheet released by the campaign highlighted Stokes'
role as head of the 197,000-member organization, stating it is the
largest law-enforcement group in the country, Stokes acknowledged
that his endorsement was a personal one, not representing the
organization. He said the group as a body would not make an
endorsement before the election.
   At the brief announcement outside Bush's Washington home, Bush
and Stokes acknowledged in response to reporters' questions that
they differ on at least one law-enforcement issue: a waiting period
to purchase a gun.
   Stokes' group favors a federal law requiring a seven-day waiting
period so that a purchaser's record can be checked before he can
buy a gun. Stokes said the waiting period is ``a common sense
approach.''
   Bush said, ``I don't favor a federal waiting period. I do favor
the states having the right to do that.'' Noting that he differs
with Stokes, he said, ``We don't agree on every single issue but
that is my position.''
   The vice president, at first bypassing further questions as he
has for the past 10 days, turned to go back into his house. But
when someone shouted a question about how Quayle was doing, Bush
turned and said heatedly:
   ``He's doing just fine. Just fine and I support him strongly.
Let me say something about that. This concept that I see in some of
these reports that I am not supportive of Dan Quayle are absolutely
ludicrous. They are ridiculous.''
   Although Bush's references to Quayle have diminished since his
running mate's debate Wednesday night with Democratic vice
presidential nominee Lloyd Bentsen, Bush said it was ``erroneous
reporting'' to suggest there is any meaning to that.
   ``He did well in that debate. He has my full support and he is
getting strong support since the debate. ... I made a good decision
and the American people saw it in that debate.''
   Bush's opponent, Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, has
intensified his criticism of Quayle since the debate, frequently
belittling him in campaign speeches. The Dukakis campaign also has
a new TV ad focusing on Quayle.
   Bush continues to hammer Dukakis as soft on crime, with another
anti-crime speech slated for Monday in New Jersey.
   On Sunday Bush was to campaign in Chicago.
</TEXT>
