<1ST_LINE>u w AM-StateSecrets Bjt   10-08 1001</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-State Secrets, Bjt,970</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wright Says Secrecy Should Never Be Used to Hide Flawed Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright's claim that he
performed a public service by criticizing a covert CIA operation in
Nicaragua has renewed debate over whether secrecy is sometimes used
to hide policies of dubious merit.
   Wright touched off a hot debate three weeks ago when he accused
the spy agency of stirring up civil unrest in Nicaragua to provoke
a crackdown by the leftist Sandinista government. As authority for
his statement, he cited ``clear CIA testimony'' before Congress.
   The House ethics committee now is investigating whether the
Texas Democrat indirectly received classified material given by the
CIA to the Intelligence Committee, then violated the chamber's
rules against public disclosure of classified information. Wright
has contended he did not.
   ``Of course we have to protect genuine government secrets,''
Wright, who as speaker has access to the nation's most sensitive
secrets, said last week. ``But a democracy must never allow secrecy
to be used as a cloak to hide bad policy from the public.''
   But those who deal routinely with top-secret information, the
members of the House and Senate intelligence committees, say the
notion that one lawmaker can decide to speak out about a covert
operation is dangerous.
   ``If you allowed every individual member to make his own
judgments about revealing classified information, it would be the
end of our system,'' said Sen. David Boren, D-Okla., chairman of
the Senate Intelligence Committee. Boren said he was not commenting
directly on the Wright case, but was speaking of broad principles.
   ``All discipline would break down, because there's virtually no
policy around here that's unanimous. Even in a democracy, there are
things that have to be kept secret,'' Boren said. Congress risks
being shut out of participation in foreign policy formulation if it
can't keep secrets, he said.
   Highly advanced U.S. technologies that cost millions of dollars
to develop are an example of secrets that must be kept,
intelligence officials say. Delicate U.S. relationships with the
intelligence services of other nations also depend on secrecy. And
lives can be at stake if secrecy of covert operations is breached,
they note.
   In the case of Wright's disclosure, House conservatives have
argued that the speaker placed members of the Nicaraguan political
opposition in jeopardy by linking them to the CIA, and handed the
Sandinistas a propaganda bonanza.
   Covert operations are actions designed to influence events in
other countries while hiding the involvement of the United States.
They range from small-scale actions, involving no more than a
handful of people, to major paramilitary efforts like U.S. support
of the Contras or of the anti-Soviet Afghan rebels.
   Most members of Congress agree that such actions sometimes are
necessary, particularly where normal diplomatic solutions are
impossible. But Boren cautioned that they must be chosen carefully.
The United States should not covertly do things that conflict with
publicly stated policies or generally held U.S. values, he said.
   It was CIA abuses in the 1960s and 70s _ planning for
assassinations of foreign leaders and domestic spying _ that led to
creation of House and Senate intelligence committees a dozen years
ago to pass judgment on the spy agency's most sensitive activities.
   In defending his comments, Wright said he was simply
highlighting that sort of duplicity in the administration's
behavior: giving lip service to peace talks between the government
and the Contras while at the same time making a secret attempt to
undermine those talks by provoking civil unrest.
   Wright's criticism also could be taken as an indirect complaint
about his own intelligence oversight panel, which under the law
would have to have been notified by the CIA about the covert action.
   Intelligence committee members have a variety of remedies if
they disagree with a proposed covert operation.
   Since they authorize all CIA spending one year at a time, they
can threaten to cut off money for the activity, or include legal
language barring it. The CIA's contingency fund, once as large as
$50 million, was cut to roughly half that amount in recent years
because of a desire for more congressional control.
   Committee members also debate covert action proposals and often
can head them off if there is widespread bipartisan opposition. The
CIA prefers to have congressional support so that it won't be left
out in the cold should a covert action become public.
   In Wright's case, he said he had known about the activity since
August 1987 and had repeatedly argued against it privately without
effect.
   Congress' least used, most potent and perhaps ultimate weapon
against a covert action is a threat to go public.
   ``That's the only real hammer,'' said Rep. George Brown,
D-Calif., who left the Intelligence Committee last year in a
dispute with the Pentagon over its classification practices.
   ``There's nothing morally wrong in supporting forces in any part
of the world that reflect the goals of a democratic country,'' said
Brown. ``But you move from that principle down a slippery slope
rapidly. You start creating forces to reflect your democratic
values. ... You let it get out of control, you start paying people
who don't give a damn about your morals.''
   Wright, he said, was speaking on behalf of a majority in
Congress who would have preferred to see U.S. interests in
Nicaragua served through a negotiated peace, and not through what
they see as provocation.
   But Sen. William Cohen, R-Maine, said Wright was wrong to go
public, even if it was in an off-the-cuff remark. Cohen was
particularly stung by the Wright incident because it doomed chances
for his bill to tighten congressional oversight of covert
operations.
   ``There is nothing to prevent him from going down and talking to
the president one-on-one, calling the head of the CIA, the
secretary of state,'' Cohen said. ``There are a number of ways to
do it. Jim Wright is not the president of the United States, and
the president bears responsibility for the decisions.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
