<DOCNO> AP881008-0100 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 1457EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CyanideEvacuation Bjt   10-08 0832</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cyanide Evacuation, Bjt,0856</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EPA Moves In, Residents Asked To Move Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NITRO, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A chemical cleanup crew planned to blow up a
rusting cylinder Sunday without knowing for sure what was inside or
if it could explode prematurely, and officials asked 3,500
residents to evacuate just in case.
   The 4-foot-long container at the defunct Artel Chemical Co.
plant could contain up to 30 pounds of hydrogen cyanide gas,
federal Environmental Protection Agency officials said.
   Hydrogen cyanide is one of the most poisonous substances made,
says Merck's Index, a directory of chemicals and drugs. As little
as 50 milligrams, or a quantity one-sixth the size of an aspirin,
can kill an adult, the book says.
   Sunday's plan was for three men to weigh the corroded tank,
carry it 100 yards to a bunker, split the sides with explosives and
start a gasoline-and-diesel fire to destroy the contents.
   But just moving the tank could trigger a reaction that would
cause an explosion before the men could reach the bunker, federal
officials said. The workers are from Jet Research Center Inc. of
Mansfield, Texas.
   As a precaution, the EPA and Mayor Don Karnes asked a third of
the town's 9,000 residents to stay away from their homes between
12:30 p.m. and 5 p.m. They planned to have 120 public officials on
hand, to bus residents to a school gymnasium and to evacuate the
elderly and handicapped to hospitals and nursing homes.
   ``A lot of people are callous toward this thing,'' Karnes said
Friday of residents of an area that has had chemical plants for
decades. ``They have been raised with chemicals and they don't see
anything wrong with this.
   ``I have asked them to go as a favor to me. I've known a lot of
these people for years. If they won't go, I've asked them to leave
their fingerprints and dental records (for identification).''
   If the cylinder is empty, all will be fine, said Jerry Heston of
the EPA, coordinator of the government's cleanup at the plant.
   ``The primary question is, `Is it full or empty or what?'''
Heston said.
   Chemical stabilizers added to the tank's contents may have
deteriorated and pressure inside may be slowly rising, Heston said.
   Hydrogen cyanide is used as a raw material by chemical
companies, forming the base for such things as acrylic waxes and
food packaging, and to kill rodents and insects in ship holds.
   A plan to destroy the cylinder Sept. 25 fell through and the
evacuation was called off when workers hired to move the container
balked. A new company was hired for Sunday's procedure.
   The Artel plant formerly was owned by Elmer Fike, a 35-year
maker of ``specialty chemicals.'' Fike openly criticized
environmental regulations, saying they were too restrictive, and
his plant often resembled a jerry-built brewery with rusted pipes
linking massive tanks.
   Artel bought the plant from Fike. When the company was unable to
pay workers, a judge ordered the plant shut. The EPA stepped in to
dispose of the 3,400 drums and barrels at the site.
   Nothing is known for certain about the tank slated for
destruction, except that it was built more than 20 years ago and
hasn't been moved or used in nearly seven years.
   ``It's probably a possibility'' that something else might be
inside, ``but Elmer (Fike) has told me that it has hydrogen cyanide
in it or nothing at all,'' Karnes said. ``I certainly have no
reason to doubt that.''
   If moving the tank triggers a reaction, the demolition experts
will have to act fast.
   ``If the cylinder starts getting hot, they will have a minute,
minute-and-a-half to put it down,'' Heston said. ``We've made
sandbag stands. They can just set it down, set up the detonation
cord, get off-site, put an airpack on and pop it.''
   ``Pop it'' means blowing one end off the tank, relieving
pressure and preventing a rupture that could send shrapnel into
other tanks at the site.
   ``We would then have hydrogen cyanide released to the
atmosphere,'' Heston said. ``We assume the whole 30 pounds would go
up in the air, and we've done air flow models to find out where it
would go. That's why we recommended the 1,000-yard evacuation
zone.''
   Forcing an evacuation hasn't been easy for Karnes.
   Some residents don't want to be bothered, either because of
their trust in the chemical industry in the heavily industrialized
Kanawha Valley, or because they agreed to leave their homes Sept.
25, when the operation was first scheduled but then canceled.
   Karnes says there are only three things that can cause another
cancellation _ bad weather, stagnant air or ``if not enough people
leave town.''
   ``I've had people calling from 1{ miles away asking me if they
should leave,'' Karnes said. ``I'm telling them they're perfectly
safe but that they can leave if they want to.
   ``I can't tell them to stay and then have a cloud go out and
kill 9,000 people.''

</TEXT>
</DOC>
