<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Latvia     10-08 0336</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Latvia,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Latvian Group Criticies Soviet Control</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates to the organizing conference of a
Latvian nationalist group on Saturday criticized management of the
Latvian economy and protested Soviet control over the Baltic
republic, a source said.
   Janis Veveris, a former political prisoner monitoring live
broadcasts of the conference in the Latvian capital, Riga, on
state-run radio and television, said particularly harsh criticism
was leveled at management of the republic's industry and
agriculture.
   Speakers also complained about pollution in Latvia and about the
Soviet takeover of the republic in 1940, Veveris said.
   The remarks came on the first day of a two-day congress of the
People's Front of Latvia. The group is similar to organizations
formed in the neighboring Baltic republics of Estonia and Lithuania
to make nationalist demands and push Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's reforms.
   The Estonian People's Front, claiming 60,000 members, held its
organizing conference Oct. 1-2, and Lithuania's is slated for Oct.
22-23.
   Tass, the official Soviet news agency, said more than 1,000
delegates, including some members of the Communist Party, were
attending the meeting in Riga. It said the group has 130,000
members. Latvia's population is 2.6 million.
   Tass said among the participants was the new president of
Latvia, Anatoly Gorbunov, who assumed his post Thursday. Also
attending, the news agency said, were members of Latvia's Communist
Party Central Committee.
   On Friday, more than 100,000 Latvians braved a rainstorm in Riga
to demonstrate in favor of the People's Front, Veveris and Tass
reported.
   Tass said the demonstration had a festive air, with participants
arriving at the forested Riga park in national costume. Entire
families attended and enjoyed improvised concerts of folk music.
Veveris said these were nationalist songs recalling Latvia's brief
independence between the world wars.
   Veveris said demonstrators waved the yellow, green and red flag
that flew in Latvia during its independence.
   Protesters also carried posters saying ``No to Russification''
and ``No Occupation,'' referring to migration of Russians into the
republic and Soviet control over the region.
</TEXT>
