<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ContaminatedCandy 1stLd-Writethru a0570 10-08 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contaminated Candy, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0570,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Says Powder Found On Candy Isn't Strychnine</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout to update with FDA saying it can't
identify the powder.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HACKENSACK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal Drug Administration tests on
candy believed to poisoned with strychnine were unable to identify
the substance and the agency is still investigating, an agency
spokesman said Saturday.
   A powder was found on a piece of candy in a package of Sunkist
Fun Fruits and Dinosaurs bought at a northern New Jersey grocery
store. Bergen County prosecutor Larry McClure said Friday that
state police laboratory tests had determined the powder was
strychnine.
   But FDA spokesman Edward Wilkens said the agency's lab in
Brooklyn, N.Y., was unable to confirm the powder was strychnine. He
said only a small piece of the candy in question was available for
testing, and officials were trying to determine why the results
from the two labs differed.
   ``Our lab isn't sure what it is,'' Wilkens said. ``They seem to
think they had enough, and if it was strychnine the lab workers
think they would have detected it.''
   FDA officials have completed an inspection of the Thomas H.
Lipton, Inc. plant in Flemington, where the candy was packaged, and
plants in California, Illinois and Oklahoma also will be inspected
for traces of strychnine, Wilkens said.
   The FBI is in charge of the investigation, he said.
   Lipton spokesman David St. Clair initially said the powder most
likely was harmless cornstarch that could have come from a mold,
which is made of cornstarch.
   McClure did not immediately respond to a message left at his
home.
   Strychnine is commonly used in rodent killer and may cause
deaths in small doses or can cause violent convulsions, loss of
muscle control, intense pain and impaired respiration.
   The candy in question was packaged Aug. 4, and the number on the
outside of the box is 8H04EF. Those boxes will still be recalled as
an extra precaution, St. Clair said.
   The batch was distributed in an area ranging from Massachusetts
to Florida and west to Ohio, McClure said Friday.
   Henry Heide Co. in New Brunswick made the candy for Lipton,
which packaged and distributed the boxes under the Sunkist label,
he said.
</TEXT>
