<DOCNO> AP881008-0105 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 1530EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NuclearPanic     10-08 0208</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nuclear Panic,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mock Exercise At Nuclear Plant Causes Panic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOMBAY, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of people living near an atomic
power plant fled in panic Saturday and squeezed onto trains leaving
the area when they mistook a drill for a real emergency, officials
said.
   At least 25,000 people living near the Tarapur Atomic Power
Plant fled after authorities declared an emergency at 5.20 a.m. and
carried out a check of evacuation procedures within a 10-mile
radius of the plant, officials said.
   The Tarapur plant, set up in 1969, is 75 miles north of Bombay.
It is India's oldest nuclear power plant.
   G.B. Pingulkar, the top government official in the area, said at
least 25,000 people fled, despite announcements beforehand that a
drill to test emergency responses would be held.
   ``People came to me asking if the plant was leaking,'' Pingulkar
said. ``I was surprised.''
   An official at the Boisar Railway Station about a mile from
Tarapur said thousands of panic-stricken residents crowded into
trains bound for Bombay after the emergency warning. ``Ticket sales
were at least four times the daily average,'' said the official,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The panic spread also to industries in Tarapur town and many
factories closed due to absenteeism.
</TEXT>
