<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FinancialFlight     10-08 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Financial Flight,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FBI: Fugitive Financial Planner Found In Taiwan, Arrested In Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TRACY FIELDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A financial planner who disappeared with $25
million and left notes of apology for his former clients was
arrested as a fugitive Saturday in Japan after being expelled from
Taiwan, FBI agents said.
   Henry Gherman, 52, has been a federal fugitive since August on
charges of embezzlement and mail fraud.
   When he was arrested by FBI agents when he got off a plane in
Tokyo, Gherman was carrying $20,000 to $30,000 in U.S. money and
``a sizable amount of Taiwanese currency,'' said FBI agent William
Wells, in charge of the agency's Miami office.
   Gherman is accused of masterminding a scheme that may have
swindled nearly 50 investors, U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen said in
a federal complaint filed Aug. 29 in federal court.
   ``Many of the victims were employees of his own firm,'' Wells
said.
   Gherman sent hand-written notes of apology to his clients when
he dropped out of sight Aug. 10.
   In addition to individual investors, Gherman had a
``longstanding pattern of embezzlement'' from about 25 professional
associations handling pension funds and other assets for members,
Lehtinen said.
   He added that the investigation of Gherman's activities
continues and additional charges are expected to be filed. He
declined to give details.
   Attorneys for a group of investos who have filed a civil suit
against Gherman said up to $25 million is missing from client
accounts.
   ``We think we'll be successful in locating some of those
funds,'' Wells said. ``We don't know how much. We just don't know
how much is left.''
   Gherman made telephone calls to his wife and to Miami attorneys
after his disappearance, but authorities did not know his
whereabouts until U.S. citizens in Taiwan reported his possible
location there, agents said. Authorities then found him and
arranged his expulsion, said Wells.
   Wells said Gherman could be brought back to Miami within a week.
But if he fights extradition, the process could take as many as 45
days, he said.
   Gherman is accused of illegally transferring clients' money to a
Miami bank account since 1978 and issuing false statements
indicating investments in money-market funds and certificates of
deposit, Lehtinen said in the federal complaint.
   The complaint cites five counts of embezzlement and two counts
of mail fraud. Gherman faces 35 years in prison and fines in excess
of $1.5 million if convicted on all counts, Lehtinen said.
</TEXT>
