<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Gun Control,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says NRA Plans Commercials Distorting His Record</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ASHEVILLE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential nominee Michael
Dukakis is trying in advance to take the steam out of what he says
are planned National Rifle Association radio commercials in North
Carolina distorting his position on gun control.
   ``It's another outrageous distortion of what I believe,''
Dukakis said. ``I've always supported the right of hunters and
sportsmen to have weapons and use them, and people to defend
themselves in their homes subject ... to state law.''
   He added, ``What I'm concerned about is teen-agers with AK-47s
and Uzis that are driving around cities in this country killing
people, and cop-killer bullets and undetectable plastic guns which
are threatening the safety of people.''
   Dukakis discussed the gun-control issue in an interview Friday
after delivering a campaign speech in this mountain city.
   His state campaign spokeswoman, Amy DeHart, said Dukakis wanted
an opportunity to clarify his stand on gun control before Monday,
when Ms. DeHart said the NRA ads would begin running.
   ``They've made a major buy (of air time) for these ads ... total
distortions of the governor's position,'' Ms. DeHart said.
   The NRA also has sent letters to its North Carolina members
criticizing Dukakis as a gun-control advocate, she said.
   David W. Conover, a federal liaison with the Washington-based
NRA, declined to discuss the organization's advertising strategy
and said he did not know whether the group would run anti-Dukakis
commercials in North Carolina.
   But Conover said the NRA was spreading the word nationwide that
Dukakis had favored restrictions on gun ownership in Massachusetts.
   ``Throughout his political career, Governor Dukakis has been
openly hostile to private firearms ownership,'' Conover said in a
telephone interview.
   He said Dukakis supported a 1976 proposal to ban private
ownership of pistols and revolvers in Massachusetts. The measure
failed in a statewide referendum, he said.
   Conover said Dukakis had modified his stand since entering the
presidential race, but that the NRA still feared he would support
gun control as president.
   Dukakis, in the interview, said, ``If somebody runs these
commercials ... then obviously I am going to fight back. And I'm
not only going to fight back to clear up the the record; I'm going
to make sure that people in this country really understand how bad
(George) Bush's record has been on crime and drugs.''
   Ms. DeHart said she had seen scripts of the ads, including one
featuring actor Charlton Heston criticizing Dukakis on gun control
and a Massachusetts prison furlough program.
</TEXT>
