<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chile     10-08 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile,0453</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Slain Demonstrator Buried; Priest Blasts Government</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Chile-Elections, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of two people killed when thousands
celebrated the defeat of President Augusto Pinochet was buried
Saturday, and the priest denounced the disappearance of dissidents
during the general's 15-year rule.
   Fourteen-year-old Luis Silva Jara ``was killed in the streets.
God doesn't like that,'' the Rev. Roberto Bolton said in a eulogy
before about 60 people at the Silva home.
   The boy was killed by an unidentified gunman Thursday, one day
after Chileans voted to reject Pinochet's bid to extend his rule
until 1997.
   Bolton criticized the torture and disappearance of government
opponents since Pinochet toppled the elected government of
President Salvador Allende, a Marxist, who died in the 1973 coup.
   Human rights groups estimate 700 people have been killed and
thousands tortured since Pinochet, the army commander, took power.
   Carlos Morales Alvarez, 31, the only other known death from the
anti-government demonstrations, was to be buried Sunday. Police
acknowlege they shot and killed Morales.
   Police also said at least 19 people leaving a huge rally staged
by opposition groups Friday were injured by soldiers firing
birdshot and pellets. One remained hospitalized at the Neurological
Institute with an eye injury, Radio Cooperativa reported.
   One American photographer was hospitalized and journalists from
several other nations walked around with bruises and bandages from
blows and kicks by police during the demonstrations.
   ``I expect to be out of here on Monday,'' said Liliana Nieto
Delrio, 31, of the Long Island-based newspaper Newsday. Ms. Nieto
said she was clubbed on the head by police and then kicked
repeatedly in the back as she lay on the ground.
   The incident occurred after dark Friday when police dispersed a
crowd of several hundred youths who left the rally and tried to
stage a demonstration near the national palace.
   A delegation of foreign journalists delivered a protest to the
National Police on Saturday. It said police attacks on more than 20
journalists in the demonstrations were unprovoked.
   After meeting the delegation, Police Col. Ivan Gonzalez said,
``There have been isolated cases'' of police attacks on reporters,
``but that type of behavior does not reflect national police
policy.''
   ``Orders have been issued again this morning that incidents like
that are not to happen again,'' Gonzalez said.
   Opposition leaders are pressing Pinochet to modify the 1980
constitution that set up Wednesday's referendum and that allows
Pinochet to remain in power through March 1990 despite his defeat.
   Presidential and congressional elections now are scheduled for
December 1989. Opposition leaders and many Chileans want them held
sooner. Pinochet has refused.
</TEXT>
