<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     10-08 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0555</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brite And Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A real estate salesman tired of
Midwest-bashing wants to give a recently introduced ``Beverly Hills
High School'' fashion line a run for its money with his own Peoria
High School getups.
   Fred Wolferman's idea for the Peoria clothing came from his
impression that residents of this Illinois River city of 120,000,
and the entire Midwest, get no respect from people living on the
East Coast or in California.
   ``I've traveled to both coasts and the perspective seems to be
that there's nothing between New York and Los Angeles,'' said
Wolferman, who lives in Kansas City, Mo. ``It's like the Midwest
doesn't exist. It really frustrates me.''
   The Peoria School Board last week sold him the rights to Peoria
High's logo.
   ``Peoria is a true heartland city,'' he said. ``Its name has all
the right connotations. I want to make it a competition and see
which is more popular, the heartland or the West Coast. If we
position it that way, the heartland is going to win.''
   Wolferman said the idea came to him when he read a newspaper
article about the Beverly Hills fashion line in which Shannon
Richey of the San Diego-based Lucas Enterprises Inc. said: ``People
are looking for something that has a lifestyle attached to it. This
is the closest most kids in Peoria will ever feel they're part of
the Beverly Hills High School attitude.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brian Corson says his sewer-cleaning job has
its rewards. He's retrieved at least 10 gold and silver necklaces,
a pair of gold earrings and a silver bracelet while on the job.
   ``The necklaces that are in good shape, I give to my wife,''
said Corson, who vacuums debris from sewers in 20 suburban
communities.
   Corson uses a small sifter he built to help him sort through the
debris and occasionally sprays water on the debris looking for
items while his truck is emptied at refuse dumps.
   After five year, he's become selective.
   ``I don't even mess with it anymore unless it's gold,'' he said.
   Among other items, Corson has found a 1951 10-centavos coin from
Argentina, a 1918 British penny, a signet ring with the initial C,
a 1914 class ring, an old police badge, a 1922 trolley token and
ornate silver spoons.
   Even without the gold and silver, the job has benefits.
   ``It's never boring,'' he said. ``A different town every day,
different people every day and no boss breathing down your back
every day.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>QUINCY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Like mother, like daughter. They both
played the same combination of family birthdays in the Megabuck
lottery game and walked away winners.
   Mary T. Crocker, of Hanover, and her daughter, Joan M. Johnson,
of Hingham, were two of four ticketholders to share Wednesday's
nearly $4 million jackpot.
   The jackpot came to $3,953,720. Each winning ticketholder will
receive, after taxes are withheld, $37,066 each year for the next
20 years.
   Neither mother or daughter have definite plans for their
winnings.
   ``We have had some health problems in the family in the past
year,'' Mrs. Johnson said. ``We needed this boost.''
   ``Now I can hire someone to do my housework,'' her mother said.
</TEXT>
