<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis     10-08 0771</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis, Mother Fight Back Against Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LEWISTON, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis and his 85-year-old
mother lashed back at George Bush on Saturday, angrily responding
to Bush's barrage of attacks on Dukakis' crime record and citing
their family's own suffering from violent crime.
   It was a moment of rare public emotion by Dukakis, who spoke of
the beating and robbery of his father at age 77, and the killing of
his brother Stelian by a hit-and-run driver at the age of 43.
   It was made even more so by the presence of the candidate's
mother Euterpe, who offered her own impassioned defense of her son.
She accused Bush of ``mangling the truth, of trying to divide us,''
of suggesting that as the son of immigrants Dukakis ``does not love
the flag quite as much,'' and of being behind letters sent to
residents of a Massachusetts town saying her brothers were
communists.
   ``Can anyone get this low?'' Dukakis' mother said.
   Campaigning on the Bates College campus where his mother and
father attended school, the Democratic presidential nominee
responded forcefully to Bush's charges _ escalated a day earlier _
that Dukakis had shown insensitivity to the victims of crime. He
said Bush was trying to divert attention from his own ``pathetic
record'' in the Reagan administration on drugs and crime.
   Bush has hammered the Massachussetts governor repeatedly over a
case in which convicted murderer Willie Horton attacked a Maryland
couple after failing to return from a furlough from a Massachusetts
prison. One of the victims of that crime have campaigned on Bush's
behalf.
   Dukakis also renewed his criticism of Bush's running mate Dan
Quayle, saying Bush has ``been running away from his choice for
vice president'' since the vice presidential debate last Wednesday,
which polls and pundits judged Quayle to have lost.
   ``Remember what he said,'' Dukakis said, recalling Bush's
comments before he selected Quayle as his running mate. ``He said,
`Watch my vice presidential decision. That will tell all.'
   ``It sure does,'' Dukakis added. ``George, you can try and run
from that decision, but you can't hide it. And you can't run away
from your own record of failure by exploiting a human tragedy for
your own political ends.''
   Dukakis, in responding to the Horton case, cited examples of
similar acts of violence committed by inmates freed from the
federal prison system, from the California prison system when
Ronald Reagan was governor, and from a Houston halfway house that
Bush has supported and praised.
   ``I don't need any lectures from Mr. Bush on crime-fighting or
on the sensitivity of compassion we must extend to the victims of
crime,'' said Dukakis.
   ``Unlike Mr. Bush, I've been a chief executive on the front
lines of fighting crime,'' Dukakis said. ``Unlike Mr. Bush, who
will not take responsibility for anything, I as chief executive
took full responsibility for that tragic Horton case and acted to
change that policy, and Mr. Bush knows it.''
   He said that under Reagan in California, a police officer and
school teacher were murdered by inmates on furlough. He added,
``Unlike Mr. Bush, Governor Reagan took full responsibility.''
   He said thousands of drug dealers are furloughed from federal
prisons every year, and that he is seeking extradition of a
convicted bank robber who was paroled from federal prison and is
wanted to stand trial in the murder of a Boston police officer.
   In the Houston case, he said one inmate raped and murdered a
minister's wife after leaving the halfway house. He said Bush
``even presented that halfway house with a presidential award _
after the tragedy occurred.''
   ``So why are we being treated these last few days to a fresh
assault on the Horton case by Mr. Bush?'' Dukakis said. ``I think
we know why. Because of his own pathetic record in the fight
against crime and drugs.''
   Dukakis and his mother spoke to a crowd of several thousand
people inside a gym at Bates College. The crowd at the school of
1,500 students was swelled by the college's annual parents' day.
The college was where his mother, who came to the United States
from Greece at age 9, graduated with honors in 1925. Dukakis'
father Panos attended the school for one year, in 1919, before
transferring to Harvard Medical School.
   Euterpe Dukakis, offering her defense against Bush's charges,
said her son ``is fighting a very, very difficult enemy, opponent.
Unfortunately, this opponent tries everything possible. So far we
have not answered very much.''
   Her husband died in 1979, six years after the attack on him.
</TEXT>
