<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Netherlands-Protest     10-08 0114</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Netherlands-Protest,0116</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>100,000 Stage Demonstration In Dutch Capital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 100,000 people waving
banners and wearing buttons saying ``Things can be different and
better'' marched Saturday in this Dutch capital to protest
government austerity measures, police said.
   The demonstration by the Federation of Dutch Trade Unions, the
country's largest labor group, was the biggest in Amsterdam in
recent years but produced no incidents or arrests, a police
spokeswoman said. She described the protest as ``super-quiet.''
   The government announced last month during its budget
presentation that the nationwide jobless rate had reached 14
percent and was unlikely to fall much in the next year while its
austerity programs were in place.
