<1ST_LINE>r w AM-UkrainianMarch     10-08 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ukrainian March,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Marchers Demand Freedom For Churches In The Ukraine</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CRISPIN Y. CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 20,000 Ukrainian-Americans
marched from the shadow of the Washington Monument to the Soviet
Embassy to deliver an appeal to Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev
for religious freedom in the Ukraine.
   The protesters, who walked the 2.7-mile route to the strains of
a World War II Ukrainian freedom fighter's march, carried signs
that said ``Free our Churches in the Ukraine.''
   The group, led by a youth in a priest's robe carrying a gold and
silver crucifix, was so large that the first part of the
demonstration was leaving the embassy before the end left the
pre-march rally site, police said.
   U.S. Park Police estimated the crowd at 20,000.
   The march was one of several events this weekend in the United
States and Canada commemorating the 1,000th anniversary of
Christianity in the Ukraine, where followers were baptized in the
city of Kiev in 988, according to National Ukrainian Millennium
Committee official Bohan Futey.
   In the letter for Gorbachev delivered to the embassy, the
organization asked for legalization of the Ukrainian Catholic and
Ukrainian Orthodox churches, which were outlawed by Joseph Stalin.
   Futey said his organization was demanding that the Soviets live
up to the religious freedom tenets of the Soviet constitution and
other international agreements.
   ``We are demanding the restoration, the opening of the Ukrainian
Orthodox and Ukrainian Catholic churches, as well as a stop to the
harassing of our brethren, be they Baptist or Pentecostal,'' he
said.
   ``Right now the people that practice the Catholic religion are
put in jail, they have to practice clandestinely. They have to meet
in the forest, in basements and at night,'' he said.
   He said there are about 50 million Ukrainians in the Soviet
Union, the majority _ 45 million _ living in the Ukraine. At least
40 million of those in the Ukraine consider themselves members of
the Ukrainian Orthodox Church, Futey said.
   The group also leveled a protest over what it termed ``the
continuing destruction of Ukraine by Russification,'' in which
Ukrainian history and culture is being appropriated as Russian to
create a pretense of unification, he said.
</TEXT>
