<DOCNO> AP881008-0121 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 1745EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mexico-Oil     10-08 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Oil,0356</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexico Says OPEC Price War Crowding It Out Of U.S. Market</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico says an OPEC price war is crowding it
out of its No. 1 market _ the United States.
   Beginning this month, OPEC governments have offered extra price
concessions to customers and moved to undercut non-cartel
competitors, including Mexico, the government oil monopoly Pemex
said Friday.
   Coupled with overproduction, the concessions ``have initiated an
undeclared, intense competition in prices among countries in the
Persian Gulf that decided to maintain or increase their market
participation, searching for new clients and seeking to displace
established commercial flows,'' Pemex said in a statement.
   Pemex on Friday announced price reductions for the United States
and said Saudi Arabia had displaced Mexico, Canada and Venezuela as
the United States' No. 1 oil supplier.
   It said production by the 13-member Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries surpassed 20 billion barrels per day in August
and September and blamed aggressive competition between OPEC
members for forcing the average price of Mexican crude on spot
markets to about $9 a barrel.
   The monopoly said as a result of the changing marketplace for
crude that it will earn less this year than the $7.9 billion
generated by oil exports in 1987.
   But Pemex said Friday that it will not increase its exports to
compensate for lost earnings and risk aggravating an already
volatile market.
   ``Mexico is ready to (hold a) dialogue both with OPEC members as
well as independent exporters with the objective of achieving
reasonable and stable prices for petroleum,'' the statement said.
   The Excelsior news service on Thursday quoted an official with
the Energy, Mines and State-Owned Industries Department as saying
Mexico had lost $2 billion in anticipated revenues so far in 1988
because of depressed market prices. The department oversees Pemex's
operations.
   Foreign exchange revenues generated by oil exports are essential
to Mexico's efforts to service its $104 billion foreign debt,
second largest in the developing world behind Brazil.
   Mexico is the world's sixth-largest oil producer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
