<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 1823EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PapyrusBoat     10-08 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Papyrus Boat,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crew In Papyrus Boat To Recreate 10,000-Year-Old Voyage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAVRION, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A papyrus boat paddled by a six-member
Greek crew set out Saturday from this Aegean port to recreate a
10,000-year-old voyage to the island of Melos.
   A black-robed bishop chanted a 20-minute blessing and a band
played music to begin the archaeological experiment to determine
how Stone Age seafarers would have made the 94-mile trip.
   Several thousand people applauded as the 21-foot open boat,
named Papyrela for the Greek word for papyrus and made of yellow
papyrus stems lashed together with rope, slipped away from the
dockside at sunset.
   The island-hopping voyage to Melos will take eight or nine days
if the weather is favorable, said Elias Mamounas, captain of the
Papyrela.
   A Greek Navy vessel and a yacht will escort the boat, said Haris
Tzalas, head of the Hellenic Institute for the Preservation of
Nautical Tradition, which organized the project.
   The earliest known Mediterranean seafarers went to Melos to
obtain supplies of obsidian, a volcanic glass prized in ancient
times as a razor-sharp cutting tool.
   American archaeologists found obsidian blades during excavations
in the 1970s at the Franchthi Cave in southern Greece. They
belonged to Mesolithic cave dwellers and were dated to around 8,000
B.C.
   Boats made of papyrus, a kind of reed, also were used in ancient
Egypt from about 5,000 B.C. The Norwegian explorer, Thor Heyerdahl,
sailed from Egypt across the Atlantic in a papyrus boat, the Ra-I.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
