<DOCNO> AP881008-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 1829EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brawley     10-08 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brawley,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tawana Brawley Stands By Her Story Despite Grand Jury Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PERKISS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associate Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black teen-ager who claimed she was raped by
six white men stood by her story Saturday and said she has
``evidence to back it up,'' despite a New York grand jury's
conclusion that she made the whole thing up.
   ``This is no hoax. It's the ugly truth that some don't want to
deal with, but I have to live with it,'' Tawana Brawley, 16, said
during a news conference.
   A dazed Miss Brawley was found Nov. 28 in a garbage bag outside
an apartment her family had recently vacated in Wappingers Falls,
75 miles north of New York City. Her body was smeared with dog
feces and marked with racial epithets.
   She said she had been held captive for four days and raped by
several white men, including one who carried a police-type badge.
She implicated several law enforcement officials in the attack.
   Miss Brawley and her mother refused to cooperate with the
investigation on the recommendation of their advisers, who had
accused authorities of a racially motivated cover-up.
   Miss Brawley appeared at Saturday's news conference with her
mother Glenda Brawley; her advisers, the Rev. Al Sharpton, C.
Vernon Mason and Alton Maddox Jr.
   ``I have a story to tell and evidence to back it up,'' Miss
Brawley said. ``I am a good student, but I am not smart enough to
fool doctors.
   ``I have suffered greatly in these last few months. This report
confirms my worst suspicions,'' she said.
   As in past appearances, Sharpton, Mason and Maddox did not allow
Miss Brawley to answer questions from reporters.
   On Thursday, a grand jury issued its report, which was based on
a seven-month investigation of the teen-ager's story.
   The panel said it found no evidence that Miss Brawley had been
sexually assaulted, and said the teen-ager herself was responsible
for the condition in which she was found after a four-day
disappearance last November.
   Miss Brawley, her mother and their advisers were in Chicago to
attend a convention of the Nation of Islam, headed by Louis
Farrakhan.
   Farrakhan has supported Brawley throughout the ordeal and
Sharpton called him the ``only credible national leader left in
black America.''
</TEXT>
