<2ND_LINE>AM-Pedestrians Killed,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Village Residents View Scene Where Five Girls Killed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYANN MROWCA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PULASKI, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crying children and bewildered neighbors
stared at chalk outlines, debris and a dangling utility pole
Saturday at the spot where five girls were killed when a speeding
car jumped a sidewalk and struck them.
   The teen-age driver has diabetes, and authorities were checking
reports that he may have suffered a seizure before the accident
Friday night, said police Chief Reed Woodward. He said no alcohol
was involved. Witnesses said the car was traveling at up to 70 mph.
   The driver and his sister, who was a passenger, were in critical
condition Saturday at two Green Bay hospitals. Pulaski, a village
with about 1,875 residents, is about 15 miles northwest of Green
Bay in northeast Wisconsin.
   ``It's going to tear us apart. Everybody's just devastated. We
knew these little girls,'' said Gina Wood, 43, who used to babysit
one of the victims.
   Witnesses told authorities the car sheared off the bottom of a
utility pole, plowed into the five girls on a sidewalk and struck a
tree. The police chief said evidence indicates the car was out of
control for about 1,500 feet.
   ``This must have happened just incredibly fast for these kids
not to get out of the way,'' Woodward said.
   He identified the victims as 13-year-olds Brenda Hylok, Laura
Karcz, Jessica McKeefry and Jodi Prokop, and Nicole Watia, 12.
   The driver, Scott C. Karcz, 17, is a distant relative of one of
the victims, Woodward said.
   The dead girls were seventh- and eighth-graders at Glenbrook
Elementary School. School officials are planning a memorial service
at Pulaski High School on Tuesday, and funerals were scheduled for
Wednesday.
   Counselors and ministers have been working to help children and
friends of the victims deal with their grief.
</TEXT>
