<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     10-08 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0468</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow Hits New England</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Two inches of snow fell near Mount Snow, Vt., and in the higher
elevations of New England Saturday, and thunder showers pelted the
central portion of the United States.
   Rain also fell in much of New England and parts of southeast New
York.
   Scattered showers and thunder storms hit south of Lake Erie and
Lake Ontario. Much of Kansas, Oklahoma and north central and
northeast Texas were covered by low clouds, fog and rain. Thunder
storms also were reported in north central Texas.
   Foggy skies shrouded the north Pacific Coast, with fair weather
prevailing over the rest of the country.
   Temperatures early Saturday were in the 30s over northeast
portions of New England. Readings were in the 40s in the northern
half of Pennsylvania, New York, New Jersey and southern parts of
New England. Temperatures were in the 50s in Oklahoma, north
central Texas, the eastern half of the central Plains, the middle
Mississippi Valley, the upper Great Lakes states, the Ohio Valley,
the middle Atlantic Coast, the northern Rockies and along the north
Pacific Coast.
   Readings were in the 80s in south central Texas and in the
southern half of Florida. Temperatures were in the 90s over the
desert Southwest. The rest of the nation had highs in the 60s and
70s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 34
degrees at Augusta, Maine, to 100 degrees at Palm Springs and
Thermal, Calif.
   The low in the nation Saturday was 19 degrees at Gunnison, Colo.
   Mansfield, Ohio, had a record low 30 degrees for the date,
breaking the previous low of 31 set in 1978.
   Sunday's forecast called for rain over the upper Ohio Valley,
the northern and central Appalachians and northern New England.
Light snow was expected over parts of northern New England.
Scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast for northeast
Texas and northwest Louisiana and showers for parts of the central
Rockies. Sunny skies were expected for the rest of the country.
   High temperatures in the 40s were forecast for the northern half
of New York state and for New England, in the 50s for the Great
Lakes, the upper Ohio Valley, the middle Atlantic Coast and the
southern half of New York state. Temperatures in the 80s were on
tap for the south half of Florida, the south half of Texas,
southern parts of the southern Plateau, western Nevada, the
southern half of the northern intermountain region and inland
portions of northern and central California. Temperatures between
90 and 105 degrees were forecast for the desert Southwest and the
desert valleys of Southern California. Highs in the 60s and 70s
were expected for the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
