<HEAD>Premier: Will Import $200 Million In Emergency Goods</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Branko Mikulic of Yugoslavia
on Saturday said the government would allow the emergency
importation of $200 million worth of food staples and other
consumer goods.
   The $200 million will be used primarily to import meat, cooking
oil, sugar and corn, whose prices have soared in recent weeks
because of drought and inflation, Mikulic said in a nationally
televised speech.
   Mikulic announced unspecified steps would be taken to protect
declining standards of living and to motivate workers to work
harder. But he also said he intended to continue with the basic
tenets of his austerity program despite widespread protests in
Montenegro republic.
   By allowing these imports, Mikulic said he hoped to dampen
inflationary pressure and demonstrate his determination to ease the
nation's economic crisis.
   The announcment came while a joint session of the state
presidency and Communist Party presidium of Montenegro republic
convened in Titograd to discuss the mass demonstrations that flared
anew this week.
   Police used clubs and tear gas Saturday to break up rallies in
Titograd and Niksic by thousands of demonstrators demanding the
ouster of Communist leaders. At least 23 people were detained and
10 injured in the incidents.
   Yugoslavia has a $21 billion foreign debt and an inflation rate
that is averaging 217 percent over the last 12 months, up from 170
percent in 1987.
</TEXT>
