<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 1927EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brandeis     10-08 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brandeis,0548</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brandeis University Reaches 40, Still Bold After All These Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WALTHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Brandeis University opened its doors 40
years ago this month with 107 students, and despite its tender age,
the private four-year college today has 3,000 students who appear
to believe youth is an asset.
   ``We have a lot more freedom in terms of policies because it
doesn't have a long tradition it's locked into,'' said senior Joel
Pomerantz, 20, of Denver, who is student Senate president.
   ``Its youth gives it an air of progressiveness. People recognize
it's a place to really explore what you believe in,'' said
Pomerantz.
   The Jewish founders of Brandeis wanted to create a nonsectarian
school in the tradition of such universities as Harvard and Notre
Dame, whose origins were religious but whose mission was quality
education.
   It was established at a time when some universities limited
enrollment of Jews and other minorities.
   ``In 1948 a lot of top universities still had quota systems for
Jews and Catholics, and blacks were hardly an issue then,'' said
David Merkowitz, spokesman for the Washington-based American
Council on Education.
   ``You don't have the same kinds of needs'' for unbiased
admission, Merkowitz said. ``But the availability of institutions
like that is important in educational diversity.''
   Today, the student body is estimated to be about 65 percent
Jewish. Thirteen percent are black, Hispanic and Asian.
   ``A place of excellence, that's why Brandeis was founded. There
were quotas against Jews, but there was a need beyond that,'' said
Brandeis President Evelyn Handler.
   Brandeis was a maverick from the start. Only two of its seven
founding trustees had been to college. The school lacked a single
large endowment but instead built itself on many small donations.
   The university is among the most expensive private colleges at
$20,000 for tuition, room and board.
   The school was named for the late U.S. Supreme Court Justice
Louis D. Brandeis. A liberal jurist and the first Jew on the high
court when he was appointed in 1916, he died in 1941.
   The small liberal arts university on the grounds of a defunct
medical school 10 miles west of Boston soon attracted to its
faculty such luminaries as Leonard Bernstein and Eleanor Roosevelt.
It began turning out such graduates as the future Rep. Stephen
Solarz, D-NY, Angela Davis and Marshal Herskovitz, the producer of
the award-winning TV show, ``thirtysomething.''
   ``There was a cerain audacity to the whole thing,'' said
Professor Lawrence Fuchs, who teaches American civilization and
politics and has been at Brandeis since 1952, serving in a variety
of administrative posts.
   ``It had such phenomenal, mercurial success. No institution
assembled a faculty of national and international standing so
quickly,'' Fuchs said.
   The question of Brandeis' Jewish identity remains an unsettled
one, however.
   When a student newspaper three years ago praised the Palestine
Liberation Organization and criticized Israel, other students
stormed its offices and labeled its staff _ one-third Jewish _
anti-Semitic.
   Just this past April, Jewish students who observe religious
dietary laws protested when the student cafeteria began serving
pork and shellfish.
   A counterprotest by students accused the protesters of hostility
toward non-Jews on the campus.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
