<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 1947EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Obit-Emig     10-08 0137</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Emig,140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>AFL-CIO Official Dead At 62</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Frank W. Emig, director of the AFL-CIO's
department of community services since 1985, died here Saturday
from cancer. He was 62.
   Emig for 20 years had headed the labor federation's efforts to
stop the spread of state right-to-work laws that forbid unions from
collecting dues from non-members that they represent in collective
bargaining contracts.
   Twenty-one states have such laws now, but only one, Louisiana,
adopted the statute between 1965 and 1985 when Emig headed the
federation's program.
   As director of community services for the AFL-CIO, Emig headed a
network of representatives in 188 cities in 37 states responsible
for coordinating blood drives, food banks and other charities,
according to Rex Hardesty, a federation spokesman.
   Emig's survivors include his widow, Rose. Plans for funeral
services were incomplete.
</TEXT>
