<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Hirohito     10-08 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito,0309</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hirohito In Stable Condition, Given Another Blood Transfusion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohito was given another blood
transfusion Saturday, as his son, Crown Prince Akihito, expressed
concern over the number of events canceled out of respect for the
ill monarch.
   For the second day, Hirohito showed no outward signs of the
hemorrhaging that caused him to vomit blood 20 days ago, imperial
officials said. But doctors said the 87-year-old emperor received
another transfusion because they believe the bleeding has not
stopped.
   Hirohito, the world's oldest living monarch, now has received a
total of 13 pints of blood since his condition worsened.
   Imperial Household Agency spokesman Kenji Maeda quoted doctors
as saying a new antibiotic apparently has helped reduce the
emperor's slight fever, which they believe is caused by an
inflammation of his bile duct.
   Maeda said the emperor's condition was stable and his jaundice
``had not progressed rapidly.''
   News reports have said Hirohito has cancer, but palace officials
have neither confirmed nor denied the reports.
   In separate meetings with Imperial Household Agency Grand
Steward Shoichi Fujimori and Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita,
Akihito, heir to the throne, said his father would be displeased
about the scores of events being canceled in deference to his
illness, officials said.
   ``We appreciate the people's warm consideration very much, but
if it affects their daily lives, I'm afraid it would not make the
emperor happy,'' Akihito was quoted as telling Fujimori.
   Events, including sports festivals, concerts, overseas trips by
government officials and visits by foreign dignitaries, have been
canceled since the emperor fell ill.
   The emperor was considered a living god until he renounced his
divinity after World War II. Under Japan's postwar constitution he
became a symbol of the state with no real political power.
</TEXT>
