<DOCNO> AP881008-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 2002EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-StorytellingFestival     10-08 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Storytelling Festival,0486</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Town Alive With Tales Of Imps, Kings</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Jym in 12th graf is cq.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LEANNE WAXMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JONESBOROUGH, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tennessee's oldest town was alive
Saturday with tales of monkey kings and devil imps at a 16-year-old
storytelling festival that has helped revive national interest in
the ancient folk art.
   Tellers from California to New York entertained about 5,000
people under large, striped tents set up on hillsides, along a
creek and near railroad tracks downtown.
   ``Aaaaargh'' screeched Brenda Wong Aoki as she became an angry
monkey king. The monkey was pulled down to the underworld but saved
from death in ``the great wok'' by eating forbidden peaches that
made him immortal.
   The San Francisco teller of tales from the Orient was among 15
featured yarn-spinners, including folk singer Pete Seeger. Seeger,
who lives in Beacon, N.Y., picked a handmade, 35-year-old banjo as
he sang of a coal miner's rebellion and the plight of American
Indians.
   ``This festival is redefining storytelling and bringing it back
to life,'' Seeger said. ``I'm just an amateur. I'm having a
wonderful time listening to these expert storytellers.''
   The three-day National Storytelling Festival is sponsored each
year by a Jonesborough group with a mouthful of a name _ the
National Association for the Preservation and Perpetuation of
Storytelling.
   The festival is bigger every year and a sixth tent was added
this year to accommodate crowds that spilled under rolled-up tent
flaps into the sun.
   Jackie Torrence, from Granite Quarry, N.C., had children in
stitches when she added her own brand of humor to the classic tale
of the selling of a soul to the devil.
   Jack, a not-so-bright poor man with only a skinny cow to sell,
runs into the devil dressed in black and sitting on a rock. He
sells the cow to the devil for a bottomless purse of gold, but he
pays later when he dies and is put in charge of the devil's 100
million caged imps.
   Amateur tellers tried their luck in the center of a small circle
of hay bales called ``The Swappin' Ground.'' Among those who got up
to tell was 9-year-old Luke Shaefer of Dexter, Mich., who spun one
about a dragon.
   ``I've got to make it a little bit slower,'' he said after he
was done. ``It's fun. I like telling stories. It's my way of having
fun.''
   Jym Kruse, 40, of Fremont, Neb., said he traveled to
Jonesborough for his second year of tip-gathering among the
masters. Kruse is a college professor, campus pastor and
storyteller in a state with no such festival, although similar
events are cropping up across the country.
   ``I come to see master tellers demonstrate how you do it well,''
he said. ``I always find new inspiration. They serve as mentors
rather than sources of information for stories.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
