<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Air Show,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Plane Crashes at Confederate Air Show; One Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARLINGEN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retired airline pilot was killed
Saturday when the vintage combat plane he was flying crashed
minutes after making a pass before an air show crowd of 20,000,
officials said.
   No other injuries were reported.
   Authorities said Max Gardner, of Fort Worth, whose age was
unavailable, was killed when the twin-engine Douglass A-20 Havack
Attack Bomber, believed to be the last of its kind, crashed about
2:45 p.m. in a cornfield about five miles south of Harlingen.
   Few people saw the crash because Gardner had already flown past
the crowd at the Valley International Airport and was about three
miles away, said Herschel Whittington of the Confederate Air Force,
an international group of pilots and air-show buffs who owned the
craft.
   The Havack Attack bomber was a fairly small workhorse used by
American, Australian and British forces during the early stages of
World War II, Whittington said.
   Harlingen police dispatcher Gale Jones said witnesses reported
seeing the plane ``flip over, do a nose dive, then hit the ground.''
   Jones also said witnesses told police the plane lost power in
one engine before crashing.
</TEXT>
