<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czechoslovakia-AIDS     10-08 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia-AIDS,0176</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Sentenced To Three Years For Spreading Disease</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man was sentenced to three years
in prison after causing ``serious health damage'' for knowingly
spreading the AIDS virus, a newspaper reported Saturday.
   The unnamed defendant, suspecting venereal disease, tested
positive for AIDS when he sought medical help two years ago, the
Lidova Demokracie (People's Democracy) newspaper reported. The man
was instructed to limit his sexual contact to one partner and to
use a condom.
   ``Several dozen witnesses, two of whom carry the virus,
testified in the case,'' said the Roman Catholic daily, which is
sanctioned by the communist government.
   The paper said it was the first such case of its type in
Czechoslovakia. The verdict is subject to an appeal.
   A positive test indicates presence of AIDS antibodies but does
not mean the person has the acquired immune deficiency syndrome.
The immune-stripping virus can be spread through sexual contact.
   Czechoslovakia has 100 registered AIDS virus carriers, the state
news agency CTK reported last month.
</TEXT>
