<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WorksiteEducation 1stLd-Writethru a0606 10-08 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Worksite Education, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0606,0624</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Learning The Three R's On The Job</HEAD>
<HEAD>RECASTS 6th graf, `Johnson arranged...' to clarify that classes
are for diplomas through General Educational Development programs
sted for General Education Diplomas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET L. CAPPIELLO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Learning on the job once meant learning
how to do the work, but some Kentucky companies are changing the
rules to give themselves an edge and their employees an education.
   There are about 400,000 illiterate adults in Kentucky, and
approximately 650,000 adults without a high school diploma, said
Pat Gleich, director of the Kentucky Literacy Commission in
Frankfort.
   Some state employers have found that the lack of education among
their workers is a drag on productivity.
   ``We had a lot of people out there that didn't finish high
school,'' said Earle Johnson, personnel administrator at the Texas
Instruments plant in Versailles. ``You're demanding more from your
people. They couldn't cope with it. They couldn't handle it.''
   Texas Instruments tested the 800 people at the plant two years
ago, Johnson said, and found 200 didn't have a high school
education. Of those, six could not read or write.
   Johnson arranged for an instructor to use a classroom in the
plant to teach classes for General Educational Development diplomas.
   The state paid for the instructor, Johnson said, while the
company provided some materials and the classroom. Students paid
the $15 class fee. At first, classes were just for employees, but
now they are open to the public.
   ``What we've found is, we end up with a person who has a much
higher self-esteem ... and they become a better employee because
they're willing to speak out better than they were before. ... It's
done a lot for the confidence of the people.
   ``It's for the individual themselves, basically. ... But we get
a benefit from it. We're not that holy. I didn't think it would
make a difference, but it does. It makes a big difference.''
   Johnson's program was a model for a similar one at Fuller
Precision Manufacturing Co. in Falmouth.
   ``I'm excited to no end'' about job-site education, Fuller
president Howard Deem said during a recent interview.
   With help from April Roberts of the Pendleton County Adult
Education Program and a literacy volunteer, Fuller offered GED and
literacy classes at the plant this year.
   Of 158 employees, about 30 signed up for both classes, Ms.
Roberts said, and 11 have so far received their GEDs.
   Deem said Fuller paid for all materials, class and test fees,
which totaled about $4,000. He also said the employees who got
their GEDs would receive a pay increase.
   Jerry Spegal, a high school dropout and assistant foreman at the
plant, said he would have taken the course without a bonus
incentive.
   ``I would say that ... when we first started going there was no
talk of a bonus, so I guess we all would've,'' Spegal said.
   Deem said the difference was phenomenal.
   ``The return on the investment has been one of the best things
I've ever done in my life,'' he said. ``We would have had to demote
these people back to janitorial services because of the quality
program we're putting in. ... How can we further the (job)
education unless they can read and write and do some basic math?''
   Even those who haven't yet graduated ``are moving up so much in
the plant, they're making money for us,'' Deem said.
   Spegal, 29, said he is thinking about attending Northern
Kentucky University.
   ``I'm not really sure ... how far I want to go. But I've got the
rest of my life to do it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
