<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 2232EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-WhistleBlowers     10-08 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Whistle Blowers,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Approves Protection For Government Whistle Blowers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Legislation to provide better protection for
government employees who report waste or fraud in their agencies
won Senate approval on Saturday and was sent to President Reagan.
   Under the bill, approved earlier in the week by the House,
government whistle blowers who feel they have been unfairly treated
would be allowed to appeal their cases directly to the Merit
Systems Protection Board, an independent body set up to review
personnel actions.
   Supporters said the legislation was needed because the Office of
Special Counsel, established to represent whistle blowers, was not
doing its job.
   The bill also would make it easier for employees to prove
improper retaliation by simplifying the elements of proof and
increasing the burden on an agency to justify its actions.
   The legislation will ``send a clear signal that retaliation
against whistle-blowers will not be tolerated'' in the federal
government, said Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., who sponsored the bill
in the Senate.
   ``If we are going to achieve a more honest and efficient
government, it is essential that we restore confidence in federal
employees that their government will respond in a fair and ethical
manner whenever they disclose wrongdoing,'' Levin said in a
statement.
   The bill won Senate approval on a voice vote as the chamber met
past midnight early Saturday, working to complete action on
numerous bills before Congress adjourns for the national elections.
   Levin predicted Reagan would sign the bill into law.
</TEXT>
