<HEAD>Rebel Leader Captured In Manila Hideout</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout with details, background. CORRECTS suspect's
first name. No pickup. ADDS byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A communist rebel leader was captured
Saturday by security forces in a raid on a suburban Manila hideout,
the military's general headquarters announced.
   Military spokesman Col. Oscar Florendo identified the rebel as
Luisito de la Cruz, a member of the outlawed Communist Party in
charge of operations in the central Luzon region north of Manila.
   Florendo described de la Cruz as a ``top-ranking'' regional
rebel leader who authorities had offered a $3,500 reward for his
capture.
   Florendo said de la Cruz, caught before dawn in a home in the
Manila suburb of Valenzuela, was undergoing interrogation at the
Camp Aguinaldo general headquarters. De la Cruz had been
underground for more than a decade.
   Military officials said de la Cruz joined the banned party in
1976 after helping organize the Association of Democratic Youth, a
breakaway faction of the rebel-backed Patriotic Youth, one of the
offshoots of the Communist-dominated National Democratic Front.
   The Communists have been waging a 19-year insurgency to
establish a Marxist state. The Front is an umbrella organization of
12 groups believed controlled by the Communist Party of the
Philippines.
   In a related development, Maj. Gen. Mariano Adalem, commander of
the Philippine Army, said the military hoped to raise up to 1
million reservists this year to ``meet any national emergency,''
including Communist rebels and right-wing extremists.
   Adalem said the reservists would be in addition to the 80,000
men expected to join a new paramilitary group, the Citizens Armed
Force Geographical Unit, which will be deployed in rural areas by
the year's end.
   The Unit, or CAFGU, is to replace other anti-Communist vigilante
and paramilitary organizations that have been accused of widespread
human rights abuses against civilians.
   Human rights groups have already complained that the CAFGUs mark
another step in what they term the ``militarization'' of Philippine
society under President Corazon Aquino.
</TEXT>
