<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NorthernIreland     10-08 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northern Ireland,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demonstration Marks 20th Anniversary Of Civil Rights March</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDONDERRY, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops and police turned
out in force Saturday to ensure a demonstration marking the 20th
anniversary of a civil rights march in Northern Ireland passed
peacefully, the Royal Ulster Constabulary said.
   No arrests or violence were reported as about 1,200 nationalist
demonstrators paraded to the center of the British province's
second largest city, said a spokesman for the RUC, Northern
Ireland's police force.
   The marchers, led by Sinn Fein political party leader Gerry
Adams, followed the route along Duke Street and Craigavon Bridge
where police and demonstrators clashed violently in 1968. Sectarian
violence since then has claimed 2,699 lives.
   Sinn Fein is the legal political wing of the outlawed Irish
Republican Army, which is waging a violent campaign to unite the
predominately Protestant province with the mainly Roman Catholic
Republic of Ireland.
   Police prevented about 100 pro-British activists from holding a
counter-demonstration along the route until after the civil rights
march ended, the police spokesman said.
</TEXT>
