<FILEID>AP-NR-10-08-88 2307EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NeedlesAshore     10-08 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Needles Ashore,0220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Could Be To Blame For Needles Washing Ashore</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of unused medical needles
that washed ashore along Palm Beach County were made for the
Department of Defense and probably were dropped overboard by a U.S.
Navy ship, an official said.
   ``They more than likely came from one of our Atlantic fleet
units,'' said Lt. Cmdr. Steve Burnett, a spokesman at fleet
headquarters in Norfolk, Va.
   He could not say why new needles would have been dumped
overboard.
   The needles had the same lot number as more than 2,000 needles
found in September along 10 miles of Flagler County beach south of
St. Augustine, state health officials said Friday.
   The needles, found Thursday along a six-mile stretch of
oceanfront from Riviera Beach to Palm Beach, were still in their
protective plastic sheaths. No syringes were found.
   Burnett said other defense units had access to the needles from
the lot, so he could not be certain the Navy was at fault.
   The Atlantic fleet rewrote its regulations in September after
five garbage bags of medical waste traced to Navy ships washed up
on North Carolina beaches in August, Burnett said. With few
exceptions, medical waste now must be held aboard ship and disposed
of in port.
</TEXT>
