<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MarcosRelative     10-08 0191</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marcos Relative,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Agents Serve Search Warrant On Ferdinand Marcos'
Son-In-Law's Estate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WOODSIDE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents searched the estate of
Ferdinand Marcos' son-in-law, allegedly looking for art works and
evidence of illegal money transfers out of the Philippines,
officials confirmed.
   FBI agent Harry Mount, in Washington D.C., said Friday that
federal agents had searched the estate of Gregorio Araneta, who is
married to Marcos' daughter Irene, but he refused to provide more
information.
   ``The only thing I can tell you is we did execute a search
warrant at that address,'' Mount said.
   CBS News, citing confidential sources, reported recently that at
least three different government agencies were involved in the
search of Araneta's home and other buildings on the estate: FBI
agents looking for art, possibly stolen from the Philippines;
Internal Revenue Service agents searching for records of reputedly
illegal money transfers; and U.S. Customs agents searching for
evidence of an aborted Marcos family conspiracy to overthrow the
government of Corazon Aquino in 1987.
   Araneta, whose telephone number is unlisted, could not be
reached for comment.
   Woodside is a small community 25 miles south of San Francisco.
</TEXT>
