<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Celebrities-Democrats     10-08 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Celebrities-Democrats,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stars Stump for the Democratic Ticket</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR J. ANASTOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Hollywood celebrities sought to add
star quality to the Democratic presidential campaign of Michael
Dukakis Saturday as their ``Star Spangled Caravan'' began a
barnstorming tour of the Pacific Northwest.
   ``Any bit of enthusiasm on the campaign would be to all of our
advantage,'' said Michael Gross, who portrays the affable father on
television's ``Family Ties.''
   About 35 actors appeared before about 800 students at the
University of Washington to campaign for the Democratic ticket and
to urge people to register to vote in November's general election.
   Saturday was the last day to register in Washington, and about
200 students signed up as Democrats, said Chris Crowley, press
secretary for the Dukakis campaign in the state.
   Gross drew the loudest response when he commented on Republican
Dan Quyale's vice presidential debate answer that he would first
say a prayer if thrust into the presidency.
   ``I can guarantee there would be a lot of other Americans on
their knees, people who have never cast a prayer in their lives,''
Gross said.
   The caravan, organized by California Assemblyman Tom Hayden,
husband of actress Jane Fonda, also planned stops in Portland,
Ore., and Sacramento, Calif. The three Pacific Coast states have 64
votes in the electoral college, nearly one-quarter of those needed
to elect a president, Hayden said.
   ``The stakes in this election are very huge. We're at the end of
the Reagan era, and the people in these states can pick the next
president,'' Hayden said in Los Angeles before the group departed.
``Voter registration in a close race can make an election. We hope
by the caravan, we will bring it to their attention.''
   For some on the tour, which included Bruce Willis, Rob Lowe,
Morgan Fairchild and Justine Bateman, it was a new experience.
   ``I've never been politically active before,'' said John
Larroqette of the television show ``Night Court.'' Larroqette said
he wrote in singer-singwriter David Bowie for president in the 1980
election.
   Gross defined the group with a term Republican candidate George
Bush has used to disparage Dukakis.
   ``As a group, we are probably more liberal than the national
average,'' he said amidst an autograph-seeking crowd that followed
the celebrities to voter registration tables at the campus rally.
   Lloyd Bridges, star of the 1960s television series ``Sea Hunt,''
stressed environmental issues in supporting Dukakis.
   ``I like pure clean water to dive in,'' he quipped. ``The
environment is very important, but not enough is being done about
it.''
</TEXT>
